{"title_page": "Maven (car sharing)", "text_new": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Maven\n| logo = Maven_car_sharing_company_logo.png\n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| trade_name = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. For multiple names in different languages, use {{Lang|[code]|[name]}}. -->\n| romanized_name = \n| former_name = \n| type = \n| traded_as = \n| ISIN = \n| ISIN2 = \n| industry = [[Automotive industry|Automotive service industry]]\n| genre = \n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| founded = <!-- if known: {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} in [[city]], state, country -->\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| hq_location = \n| hq_location_city = [[Detroit, Michigan]]\n| hq_location_country = \n| num_locations = \n| num_locations_year = <!-- Year of num_locations data (if known) -->\n| areas_served = [[United States]]<br>[[Canada]]\n| key_people = Sigal Cordeiro, Vice President of Maven and GM Urban Mobility<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wayland|first1=Michael|title=\nGM appoints marketing veteran to lead Maven|url=https://www.autonews.com/executives/gm-appoints-marketing-veteran-lead-maven |publisher=Automotive News|date=}}</ref>\n| products = \n| brands = \n| production = \n| production_year = <!-- Year of production data (if known) -->\n| services = [[Car sharing]]<br>[[Peer-to-peer car sharing]]<br>[[Gig economy|Gig rentals]]\n| revenue = \n| revenue_year = <!-- Year of revenue data (if known) -->\n| operating_income = \n| income_year = <!-- Year of operating_income data (if known) -->\n| net_income = <!-- or: | profit = -->\n| net_income_year = <!-- or: | profit_year = --><!-- Year of net_income/profit data (if known) -->\n| aum = <!-- Only for financial-service companies -->\n| assets = \n| assets_year = <!-- Year of assets data (if known) -->\n| equity = \n| equity_year = <!-- Year of equity data (if known) -->\n| owner = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| members = \n| members_year = <!-- Year of members data (if known) -->\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = [[General Motors]]\n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| module = <!-- Used to embed other templates -->\n| ratio = <!-- Basel III ratio; used for banks only -->\n| rating = <!-- Credit rating; used for banks only -->\n| website = {{url|http://maven.com}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Maven''' is a [[car sharing]] service launched by [[General Motors]] (GM) in 2016. It provides services such as [[carsharing]] and [[peer-to-peer car sharing]] for personal use and also rents to drivers of [[Temporary work|gig economy]] professions such as [[Uber]] and [[Lyft]]. It operates in select cities in the United States and Canada and has been described as an AirBnB for cars. \n\n==History==\n\nMaven was announced in January 2016 and has been referred to as the AirBnB for cars.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hawkins |first1=Andrew J. |title=General Motors wants its customers to rent their cars to other people |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/7/24/17609368/general-motors-car-sharing-rent-peer-to-peer-maven-price-gm |publisher=The Verge |date=24 July 2018}}</ref> At the time of its launch, Maven's team consisted of 40 people.<ref name=\"Verge2\">{{cite news |last1=Hawkins |first1=Andrew J. |title=GM launches Maven, a car-sharing service to compete with Zipcar |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/1/21/10802240/gm-maven-car-sharing-service-price-launch-date-michigan |publisher=The Verge |date=21 January 2016}}</ref> The year prior, GM had purchased the assets of then defunct [[Sidecar (company)|Sidecar]] after that company failed to gain ground on [[Lyft]] and [[Uber]].<ref name=\"WP1\">{{cite news |last1=Read |first1=Richard |title=GM Launches Maven Car-Sharing Service, Buys Remains Of Uber Competitor, Sidecar |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/cars/gm-launches-maven-car-sharing-service-buys-remains-of-uber-competitor-sidecar/2016/01/21/ecc3678a-c065-11e5-98c8-7fab78677d51_story.html |publisher=The Washington Post |date=21 January 2016}}</ref>  \n\nMaven launched as a pilot program at the [[University of Michigan at Ann Arbor]] and expanded to other cities a few weeks later.<ref name=\"MLive1\">{{cite news |last1=Muller |first1=David |title=GM launches Maven car-sharing service in Ann Arbor, other cities to come |url=https://www.mlive.com/auto/2016/01/gm_launches_maven_car-sharing.html |publisher=MLive |date=21 January 2016}}</ref> In August 2017, Maven was announced as the exclusive car sharing partner for the [[University of Southern California]] in Los Angeles.<ref name=freep1>{{cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/money/cars/general-motors/2017/08/11/gm-maven-usc/561112001/|title=GM's Maven will provide cars to students at USC|publisher=freep.com |date=August 11, 2017|accessdate=December 11, 2017}}</ref> Maven also launched Maven Gig, a rental service for people who work in the gig economy such as drivers of [[Uber]], [[Lyft]], and [[Uber Eats]].<ref name=\"Cars.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cars.com/articles/gms-maven-gig-expands-ride-sharing-reach-1420696627263/|title=GM's Maven Gig Expands Ride-Sharing Reach |date=August 11, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy 2018, Maven had 190,000 members and expanded to major cities across the United States.<ref name=\"DN1\">{{cite news |last1=Naughton |first1=Nora |title=Maven car-sharing creates 'side hustle' for Metro Detroit dad |url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/business/autos/general-motors/2018/12/30/maven-peer-sharing-creates-side-hustle-metro-detroit-dad/2362545002/ |publisher=The Detroit News |date=30 December 2018}}</ref> It had also entered the Australian market where it initially provided gig-economy rentals prior to adding personal car sharing services.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dowling |first1=Joshua |title=Cars on demand to replace vehicle ownership for a new generation of drivers |url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/consumer-affairs/cars-on-demand-to-replace-vehicle-ownership-for-a-new-generation-of-drivers-20190524-p51r0d.html |publisher=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=26 May 2019}}</ref> It operated in a total of 17 cities in North America as of May 2019.<ref name=\"TC1\">{{cite news |last1=Korosec |first1=Kirsten |title=GM\u2019s car-sharing service Maven to exit eight cities |url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/05/20/gms-car-sharing-service-maven-to-exit-eight-cities/ |publisher=TechCrunch |date=20 May 2019}}</ref> Maven exited select cities in 2019 based on market analysis by GM,<ref name=\"WSJ1\">{{cite news |last1=Colias |first1=Mike |title=GM Scales Back Maven Car-Sharing Business |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/gms-car-sharing-business-to-end-service-in-eight-of-its-17-north-american-cities-11558382917 |publisher=The Wall Street Journal |date=20 May 2019}}</ref> and announced it would focus on cities with the strongest demand and growth.<ref name=\"TC1\"/> Maven also partnered with [[NRG Energy|EVgo]] in 2019 to provide fast charging stations for users of Maven electric vehicles.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Edelstein |first1=Stephen |title=Maven and EVgo Partner on Electric Car Charging for Ride-Hailing Drivers |url=https://www.thedrive.com/tech/20067/maven-and-evgo-partner-on-electric-car-charging-for-ride-hailing-drivers |publisher=The Drive |date=12 April 2018}}</ref> \n\n==Services==\n\nMaven provides car sharing services, including car sharing for personal use and rentals for drivers of [[Temporary work|gig economy]] professions such as [[Uber]] and [[Lyft]]. It uses an app for people to search for and book rentals. It is also used to control certain features of the car such as remote start and unlocking of doors.<ref name=\"TC1\"/> \n\nMaven also allows individual owners of General Motors vehicles to share their cars by the hour or daily through a peer-to-peer car sharing service.<ref name=\"TheVerge\">{{cite news |last1=O'Kane |first1=Sean |title=GM is letting more people rent their cars for money |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/10/23/18014166/maven-gm-peer-car-rental-sharing |publisher=The Verge |date=23 October 2018}}</ref>  Owners receive sixty percent of the rental cost and also get liability insurance. Vehicles must be newer model GM vehicles and go through an on-boarding process which includes installation of a keyless entry system.<ref name=\"TheVerge\"/> \n\nMaven Gig was launched in 2017 and rents vehicles to people who work in the gig economy such as drivers of [[Uber]], [[Lyft]], and [[Uber Eats]].<ref name=\"Cars.com\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.maven.com}}\n\n{{General Motors}}\n{{Vehicle rental brands}}\n\n[[Category:General Motors]]\n[[Category:Carsharing]]\n[[Category:Car rental companies of the United States]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox company\n| name = Maven\n| logo = Maven_car_sharing_company_logo.png\n| logo_size = \n| logo_alt = \n| logo_caption = \n| image = \n| image_size = \n| image_alt = \n| image_caption = \n| trade_name = \n| native_name = \n| native_name_lang = <!-- Use ISO 639-1 code, e.g. \"fr\" for French. For multiple names in different languages, use {{Lang|[code]|[name]}}. -->\n| romanized_name = \n| former_name = \n| type = \n| traded_as = \n| ISIN = \n| ISIN2 = \n| industry = [[Automotive industry|Automotive service industry]]\n| genre = \n| fate = \n| predecessor = \n| successor = <!-- or: | successors = -->\n| founded = <!-- if known: {{Start date and age|YYYY|MM|DD}} in [[city]], state, country -->\n| founder = <!-- or: | founders = -->\n| defunct = <!-- {{End date|YYYY|MM|DD}} -->\n| hq_location = \n| hq_location_city = [[Detroit, Michigan]]\n| hq_location_country = \n| num_locations = \n| num_locations_year = <!-- Year of num_locations data (if known) -->\n| areas_served = [[United States]]<br>[[Canada]]\n| key_people = Sigal Cordeiro, Vice President of Maven and GM Urban Mobility<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wayland|first1=Michael|title=\nGM appoints marketing veteran to lead Maven|url=https://www.autonews.com/executives/gm-appoints-marketing-veteran-lead-maven |publisher=Automotive News|date=}}</ref>\n| products = \n| brands = \n| production = \n| production_year = <!-- Year of production data (if known) -->\n| services = [[Car sharing]]<br>[[Peer-to-peer car sharing]]<br>[[Gig economy|Gig rentals]]\n| revenue = \n| revenue_year = <!-- Year of revenue data (if known) -->\n| operating_income = \n| income_year = <!-- Year of operating_income data (if known) -->\n| net_income = <!-- or: | profit = -->\n| net_income_year = <!-- or: | profit_year = --><!-- Year of net_income/profit data (if known) -->\n| aum = <!-- Only for financial-service companies -->\n| assets = \n| assets_year = <!-- Year of assets data (if known) -->\n| equity = \n| equity_year = <!-- Year of equity data (if known) -->\n| owner = <!-- or: | owners = -->\n| members = \n| members_year = <!-- Year of members data (if known) -->\n| num_employees = \n| num_employees_year = <!-- Year of num_employees data (if known) -->\n| parent = [[General Motors]]\n| divisions = \n| subsid = \n| module = <!-- Used to embed other templates -->\n| ratio = <!-- Basel III ratio; used for banks only -->\n| rating = <!-- Credit rating; used for banks only -->\n| website = {{url|http://maven.com}}\n| footnotes = \n}}\n\n'''Maven''' is a [[car sharing]] service launched by [[General Motors]] (GM) in 2016. It provides services such as [[carsharing]] and [[peer-to-peer car sharing]] for personal use and also rents to drivers of [[Temporary work|gig economy]] professions such as [[Uber]] and [[Lyft]]. It operates in select cities in the United States and Canada and has been described as an AirBnB for cars. \n\n==History==\n\nMaven was announced in January 2016 and has been referred to as the AirBnB for cars.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hawkins |first1=Andrew J. |title=General Motors wants its customers to rent their cars to other people |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/7/24/17609368/general-motors-car-sharing-rent-peer-to-peer-maven-price-gm |publisher=The Verge |date=24 July 2018}}</ref> At the time of its launch, Maven's team consisted of 40 people.<ref name=\"Verge2\">{{cite news |last1=Hawkins |first1=Andrew J. |title=GM launches Maven, a car-sharing service to compete with Zipcar |url=https://www.theverge.com/2016/1/21/10802240/gm-maven-car-sharing-service-price-launch-date-michigan |publisher=The Verge |date=21 January 2016}}</ref> The year prior, GM had purchased the assets of then defunct [[Sidecar (company)|Sidecar]] after that company failed to gain ground on [[Lyft]] and [[Uber]].<ref name=\"WP1\">{{cite news |last1=Read |first1=Richard |title=GM Launches Maven Car-Sharing Service, Buys Remains Of Uber Competitor, Sidecar |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/cars/gm-launches-maven-car-sharing-service-buys-remains-of-uber-competitor-sidecar/2016/01/21/ecc3678a-c065-11e5-98c8-7fab78677d51_story.html |publisher=The Washington Post |date=21 January 2016}}</ref>  \n\nMaven launched as a pilot program at the [[University of Michigan at Ann Arbor]] and expanded to other cities a few weeks later.<ref name=\"MLive1\">{{cite news |last1=Muller |first1=David |title=GM launches Maven car-sharing service in Ann Arbor, other cities to come |url=https://www.mlive.com/auto/2016/01/gm_launches_maven_car-sharing.html |publisher=MLive |date=21 January 2016}}</ref> In August 2017, Maven was announced as the exclusive car sharing partner for the [[University of Southern California]] in Los Angeles.<ref name=freep1>{{cite web|url=https://www.freep.com/story/money/cars/general-motors/2017/08/11/gm-maven-usc/561112001/|title=GM's Maven will provide cars to students at USC|publisher=freep.com |date=August 11, 2017|accessdate=December 11, 2017}}</ref> Maven also launched Maven Gig, a rental service for people who work in the gig economy such s drivers of [[Uber]], [[Lyft]], and [[Uber Eats]].<ref name=\"Cars.com\">{{cite web|url=https://www.cars.com/articles/gms-maven-gig-expands-ride-sharing-reach-1420696627263/|title=GM's Maven Gig Expands Ride-Sharing Reach |date=August 11, 2017|accessdate=February 19, 2018}}</ref>\n\nBy 2018, Maven had 190,000 members and expanded to major cities across the United States.<ref name=\"DN1\">{{cite news |last1=Naughton |first1=Nora |title=Maven car-sharing creates 'side hustle' for Metro Detroit dad |url=https://www.detroitnews.com/story/business/autos/general-motors/2018/12/30/maven-peer-sharing-creates-side-hustle-metro-detroit-dad/2362545002/ |publisher=The Detroit News |date=30 December 2018}}</ref> It had also entered the Australian market where it initially provided gig-economy rentals prior to adding personal car sharing services.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Dowling |first1=Joshua |title=Cars on demand to replace vehicle ownership for a new generation of drivers |url=https://www.smh.com.au/business/consumer-affairs/cars-on-demand-to-replace-vehicle-ownership-for-a-new-generation-of-drivers-20190524-p51r0d.html |publisher=The Sydney Morning Herald |date=26 May 2019}}</ref> It operated in a total of 17 cities in North America as of May 2019.<ref name=\"TC1\">{{cite news |last1=Korosec |first1=Kirsten |title=GM\u2019s car-sharing service Maven to exit eight cities |url=https://techcrunch.com/2019/05/20/gms-car-sharing-service-maven-to-exit-eight-cities/ |publisher=TechCrunch |date=20 May 2019}}</ref> Maven exited select cities in 2019 based on market analysis by GM,<ref name=\"WSJ1\">{{cite news |last1=Colias |first1=Mike |title=GM Scales Back Maven Car-Sharing Business |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/gms-car-sharing-business-to-end-service-in-eight-of-its-17-north-american-cities-11558382917 |publisher=The Wall Street Journal |date=20 May 2019}}</ref> and announced it would focus on cities with the strongest demand and growth.<ref name=\"TC1\"/> Maven also partnered with [[NRG Energy|EVgo]] in 2019 to provide fast charging stations for users of Maven electric vehicles.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Edelstein |first1=Stephen |title=Maven and EVgo Partner on Electric Car Charging for Ride-Hailing Drivers |url=https://www.thedrive.com/tech/20067/maven-and-evgo-partner-on-electric-car-charging-for-ride-hailing-drivers |publisher=The Drive |date=12 April 2018}}</ref> \n\n==Services==\n\nMaven provides car sharing services, including car sharing for personal use and rentals for drivers of [[Temporary work|gig economy]] professions such as [[Uber]] and [[Lyft]]. It uses an app for people to search for and book rentals. It is also used to control certain features of the car such as remote start and unlocking of doors.<ref name=\"TC1\"/> \n\nMaven also allows individual owners of General Motors vehicles to share their cars by the hour or daily through a peer-to-peer car sharing service.<ref name=\"TheVerge\">{{cite news |last1=O'Kane |first1=Sean |title=GM is letting more people rent their cars for money |url=https://www.theverge.com/2018/10/23/18014166/maven-gm-peer-car-rental-sharing |publisher=The Verge |date=23 October 2018}}</ref>  Owners receive sixty percent of the rental cost and also get liability insurance. Vehicles must be newer model GM vehicles and go through an on-boarding process which includes installation of a keyless entry system.<ref name=\"TheVerge\"/> \n\nMaven Gig was launched in 2017 and rents vehicles to people who work in the gig economy such as drivers of [[Uber]], [[Lyft]], and [[Uber Eats]].<ref name=\"Cars.com\"/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website|http://www.maven.com}}\n\n{{General Motors}}\n{{Vehicle rental brands}}\n\n[[Category:General Motors]]\n[[Category:Carsharing]]\n[[Category:Car rental companies of the United States]]\n", "name_user": "Grayfell", "label": "safe", "comment": "Restoring positive from previous revert", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maven_(car_sharing)"}
{"title_page": "Joan Crawford filmography", "text_new": "{{short description|A list of film appearances of American actress Joan Crawford}}\n[[File:Joan Crawford in Mildred Pierce trailer.jpg|200px|thumb|right|Crawford in the trailer for ''[[Mildred Pierce (film)|Mildred Pierce]]'' (1945)]]\n[[File:Joan Crawford in Humoresque, 1946.jpg|190px|thumb|right|Crawford in ''[[Humoresque (1946 film)|Humoresque]]'' (1946)]]\n[[File:The Damned Don't Cry! 1.jpg|200px|thumb|right|L-R: Crawford, [[Steve Cochran]], [[Richard Egan (actor)|Richard Egan]], and [[David Brian]] in ''[[The Damned Don't Cry]]'' (1950)]]\n[[File:Bette Davis and Joan Crawford in Whatever Happened to Baby Jane trailer.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Crawford and [[Bette Davis]] in ''[[What Ever Happened to Baby Jane? (film)|What Ever Happened to Baby Jane?]]'' (1962)]]\n\nThe '''Joan Crawford filmography''' lists the film appearances of American actress '''[[Joan Crawford]]''', who starred in numerous [[film|motion picture]]s throughout a lengthy career that spanned nearly five decades.\n\nShe made her film debut in ''[[Lady of the Night]]'' (1925), as a [[body double]] for film star [[Norma Shearer]]. She appeared in several other films before she made her major breakthrough playing [[Lon Chaney, Sr.|Lon Chaney]]'s love interest in the 1927 [[horror film]], ''[[The Unknown (1927 film)|The Unknown]]''. Her major success in ''[[Our Dancing Daughters]]'' (1928) made her a popular [[flapper]] of the late 1920s. Her first sound film, ''[[Untamed (1929 film)|Untamed]]'' (1929), was a critical and box office success.\n\nCrawford would become a highly popular actress throughout the 1930s, as a [[leading lady]] for [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]. She starred in a series of \"[[rags to riches|rags-to-riches]]\" films that were extremely popular during the [[Great Depression|Depression]]-era, most especially with women. Her popularity rivaled fellow MGM actresses, including [[Greta Garbo]], [[Norma Shearer]], and [[Jean Harlow]]. She appeared in eight movies with [[Clark Gable]], including romantic drama ''[[Possessed (1931 film)|Possessed]]'' (1931), musical film ''[[Dancing Lady]]'' (1933), romantic comedy ''[[Love on the Run (1936 film)|Love on the Run]]'' (1936), and romantic drama ''[[Strange Cargo (1940 film)|Strange Cargo]]'' (1940), among others.<!-- Ben-Hur: A Tale of the Christ (1925)\nThe Merry Widow (1925)\nPossessed (1931)\nDance, Fools, Dance (1931)\nLaughing Sinners (1931)\nScreen Snapshots (1932)\nDancing Lady (1933)\nForsaking All Others (1934)\nChained (1934)\nLove on the Run (1936)\nStrange Cargo (1940)\nhttp://www.imdb.com/search/title?roles=nm0001076,nm0000022&title_type=feature,tv_episode,video,tv_movie,tv_special,mini_series,documentary,game,short\n --> In 1937, she was proclaimed the first \"Queen of the Movies\" by ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'' magazine, but her popularity soon waned. After her films ''[[The Bride Wore Red]]'' (1937) and ''[[Mannequin (1937 film)|Mannequin]]'' (1938) proved to be expensive failures, in May 1938, Crawford \u2013 along with [[Greta Garbo]], [[Katharine Hepburn]], [[Fred Astaire]], [[Kay Francis]], and many others \u2013 was labeled [[Box Office Poison (magazine article)|box office poison]]; an actor whose \"box office draw is nil\".\n\nCrawford managed to make a comeback in the comedy ''[[The Women (1939 film)|The Women]]'' (1939), opposite an all-star female only cast. On July 1, 1943, Crawford left MGM and signed an exclusive contract with [[Warner Bros.|Warner Brothers]], where she became a rival of [[Bette Davis]]. After a slow start with the studio, she received critical and commercial acclaim for her performance in drama ''[[Mildred Pierce (film)|Mildred Pierce]]'' (1945). The film earned her an [[Academy Award for Best Actress]]. From 1946 to 1952, Crawford appeared in a series of critical and box office successes, including the musical drama ''[[Humoresque (1946 film)|Humoresque]]'' (1946); film noirs ''[[Possessed (1947 film)|Possessed]]'' (1947, for which she received a second Academy Award nomination) and ''[[Flamingo Road (film)|Flamingo Road]]'' (1949); drama ''[[The Damned Don't Cry]]'' (1950); and romantic comedy ''[[Goodbye, My Fancy]]'' (1951), among others. She received a third \u2013 and final \u2013 Academy Award nomination for her performance in the thriller ''[[Sudden Fear]]'' (1952).\n\nIn 1953, Crawford starred in the musical ''[[Torch Song (1953 film)|Torch Song]]'', her final film role for MGM. Her next film ''[[Johnny Guitar]]'' (1954), although not a major hit, is one of Crawford's most popular films among her fans. During the latter half of the 1950s, Crawford starred in a series of [[B-movie]]s, including romantic dramas ''[[Female on the Beach]]'' (1955) and ''[[Autumn Leaves (film)|Autumn Leaves]]'' (1956). In 1962, Crawford was teamed with [[Bette Davis]] in a film adaptation of ''[[What Ever Happened to Baby Jane? (film)|What Ever Happened to Baby Jane?]]''. The [[thriller film]] was a box office hit, and briefly revived Crawford's career. Her final film performance was in the [[United Kingdom|British]] [[science fiction film]], ''[[Trog]]'' (1970).\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Feature films===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders sortable\"\n|+ Silent films\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Director\n! Studio\n|-\n| 1925 || ''[[Lady of the Night]]'' || Double for [[Norma Shearer]]<ref name=\"uncredited\">Uncredited</ref> || [[Monta Bell]] || [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n|-\n| 1925 || ''[[Proud Flesh (film)|Proud Flesh]]'' || Party Guest<ref name=\"uncredited\" /> || [[King Vidor]] || [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n|-\n| 1925 || ''[[A Slave of Fashion]]''<sup>\u2021</sup> || Mannequin<ref name=\"uncredited\" /> || [[Hobart Henley]] || [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n|-\n| 1925 || ''[[The Merry Widow (1925 film)|The Merry Widow]]'' || Ballroom Dancer<ref name=\"uncredited\" /> || [[Erich von Stroheim]] || [[Metro-Goldwyn-Mayer]]\n|-\n| 1925 || ''[[Pretty Ladies]]'' || Bobby, a Showgirl<ref na