9 - Pacific County Public Health and Human Services |publisher=Pacificcountyhealthdepartment.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Pend Oreille\n| 0\n| 0\n| ?\n|Updated: 12:45 pm  04/01/20<ref name=\"netchd\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Pierce\n| 423\n| 7\n| ?\n|Updated: 1:40 pm  04/01/20<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.tpchd.org/healthy-people/diseases/covid-19-pierce-county-cases/|title=COVID-19 in Pierce County &#124; Tacoma-Pierce County Health Department|website=www.tpchd.org}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | San Juan\n| 4\n| 0\n| ?\n|Updated: 03/31/20<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.sanjuanco.com/1682/COVID-19-SJC-Case-Count|title=COVID-19 SJC Case Count &#124; San Juan County, WA|website=www.sanjuanco.com}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Skagit\n| 143\n| 4\n| ?\n|Updated: 2:45 pm  04/01/20<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.skagitcounty.net/Departments/HealthDiseases/coronavirus.htm|title=Novel Coronavirus Outbreak (COVID19)|website=www.skagitcounty.net}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Skamania\n| 1\n| 0\n| ?\n|Updated: 11:59 pm  03/28/20<ref>https://www.doh.wa.gov/emergencies/coronavirus</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Snohomish\n| 1,304\n| 40\n| 562\n|Updated: 2:00 pm  04/01/20<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.snohd.org/499/COVID-19-Case-Count-Info|title=COVID-19 Case Count Info &#124; Snohomish Health District, WA|website=www.snohd.org}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Spokane\n| 145\n| 4\n| ?\n|Updated: 12:00 pm  03/31/20<ref>{{cite web|url=https://srhd.org/covid19cases|title=Spokane County COVID-19 Case Information|website=SRHD}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Stevens\n| 4\n| 0\n| ?\n|Updated: 12:45 pm  04/01/20<ref name=\"netchd\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Thurston\n| 51\n| 0\n| ?\n|Updated: 3:00 pm  04/01/20<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thurstoncountywa.gov/phss/Pages/coronavirus.aspx|title=Thurston County &#124; Public Health & Social Services &#124; Corona Virus|website=www.thurstoncountywa.gov}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Wahkiakum\n| 0\n| 0\n| ?\n| Updated: 04/01/20<ref name=\"pchd\"/>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Walla Walla\n| 7\n| 0\n| 1\n|Updated: 5:00 pm  03/31/20<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.co.walla-walla.wa.us/government/health_department/index.php|title=Walla Walla County Department of Community Health|website=www.co.walla-walla.wa.us}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Whatcom\n| 144\n| 8\n| ?\n|Updated: 12:00 pm  04/01/20<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whatcomcounty.us/3329/Novel-Coronavirus-COVID-19|title=Novel Coronavirus (COVID-19) &#124; Whatcom County, WA - Official Website|website=www.whatcomcounty.us}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Whitman\n| 10\n| 0\n| 1<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khq.com/coronavirus/woman-becomes-first-whitman-county-resident-to-test-positive-for/article_3fca7cda-6c69-11ea-ae67-83d8506c6281.html |title=Woman becomes first Whitman County resident to test positive for COVID-19 &#124; Coronavirus |publisher=khq.com |date= |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n|Updated: 12:06 pm  04/01/20<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitmancountypublichealth.org/covid-19.html|title=COVID-19|website=Whitman County Public Health}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Yakima\n| 202\n| 3\n| 188\n|Updated: 4:36 pm  03/31/20<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.yakimacounty.us/2323/COVID-19|title=COVID-19 &#124; Yakima County, WA|website=www.yakimacounty.us}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | (Unassigned)\n| 387\n| 0<ref>https://www.doh.wa.gov/emergencies/coronavirus shows 0 deaths under the unassigned category. March 22, 2020</ref>\n| \n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Cases with no assigned county\n\n|- class=\"sortbottom\"\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | Total\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 5,967\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | 250\n! style=\"text-align:right;\" | ?\n! style=\"text-align:left;\"  | Per: updates from counties\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* {{cite news |title=How a Seattle suburb responded after becoming the epicenter of the U.S. coronavirus outbreak |date=March 16, 2020 |newspaper=The Seattle Times |first=Paige |last=Cornwell |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/eastside/how-a-seattle-suburb-responded-after-becoming-the-epicenter-of-the-u-s-coronavirus-outbreak/}}\n* {{cite news|title=Where coronavirus outbreak started in Washington state, officials see hope as cases appear to be leveling off|newspaper=The Washington Post|author=Robert Klemko|date=March 26, 2020|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/national/coronavirus-washington-state-leveling-off/2020/03/26/682790e6-6f6b-11ea-a3ec-70d7479d83f0_story.html}}\n* {{cite news|newspaper=The New York Times|title=Coronavirus Slowdown in Seattle Suggests Restrictions Are Working|author=Mike Baker|date=March 29, 2020|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/29/us/seattle-washington-state-coronavirus-transmission-rate.html}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|COVID-19 pandemic in Washington (state)}}\n* [https://www.coronavirus.wa.gov/ Official State of Washington coronavirus information page]\n* [https://www.arcgis.com/apps/MapSeries/index.html?appid=84b17c2a2af8487f97a244b6126834c2 COVID tracker map], Washington State Department of Health\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States}}\n{{Portal bar|Coronavirus disease 2019|Medicine|Pandemic|United States|Viruses}}\n\n[[Category:2020 in Washington (state)|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States by state|Washington]]\n[[Category:2020 disasters in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:Health in Washington (state)]]\n[[Category:February 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:January 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:March 2020 events in the United States|Coronavirus pandemic]]\n[[Category:April 2020 events in the United States|coronavirus pandemic]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of viral ongoing pandemic in Washington}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use American English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Current disaster|event=disease pandemic|date=January 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Washington\n| map1 = COVID-19_Cases_by_counties_of_Washington_(state).svg\n| legend1 = Map of the outbreak in Washington <br />\n(as of March 27): {{legend|#BB2919|Confirmed cases}}\n| map2 =\n| legend2 =\n| map3 =\n| legend3 =\n| disease = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location = [[Washington (state)|Washington]], U.S.\n| first_case = [[Everett, Washington|Everett]]\n| arrival_date = January 21, 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=21|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]\n| confirmed_cases = [[2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Washington_(state)#Cases_by_county| 5,707]]\n| suspected_cases =\n| recovery_cases = \n| deaths = [[2020_coronavirus_pandemic_in_Washington_(state)#Cases_by_county| 229]]\n| territories =\n| total_ili =\n| website = {{URL|https://www.coronavirus.wa.gov}}\n}}\nThe first confirmed case of [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|the global pandemic]] of [[coronavirus disease 2019]] (COVID-19) [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in the United States|in the United States]] was announced by the state of [[Washington (state)|Washington]] on January 21, 2020. Washington made the first announcement of a death from the disease in the U.S. on February 29 and later announced that two deaths there on February 26 were also due to COVID-19. Until mid-March, Washington had the highest absolute number of confirmed cases and the highest number per capita of any state in the country,<ref>{{cite news |title=New Orleans is second only to Seattle in COVID-19 cases per capita |first=Mike |last=Perlstein |url=https://www.wwltv.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/perl-stats-story/289-f2e70da4-3e5b-48b5-8684-a0dd5dc0361d |newspaper=4WWL |date=March 16, 2020 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> when it was surpassed by [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in New York (state)|New York state]]. Many of the deceased were residents of a nursing home in [[Kirkland, Washington|Kirkland]], an [[Eastside (King County, Washington)|Eastside]] suburb of [[Seattle]] in [[King County, Washington|King County]].\n\nWashington had 5,632 confirmed cases as of April 1, 2020 and a total of 225 confirmed deaths.(See table below). Public health experts agree that the true number of cases in the state is much greater than the number that have been confirmed by laboratory tests. It is very difficult to know the true number since most people experience mild illness and testing is not widely available.<ref name=official_DOH_COVID>{{cite web |url=https://www.doh.wa.gov/emergencies/coronavirus |title=2019 Novel Coronavirus Outbreak (COVID-19) |date=March 28, 2020 |website=Washington State Department of Health |access-date=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\nGovernor [[Jay Inslee]] issued a statewide [[stay-at-home order]] on March 23 to last at least two weeks.<ref>{{cite web|author=Associated Press |url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/23/washington-governor-issues-two-week-stay-at-home-order/ |title=Washington governor issues two-week stay-at-home order |publisher=Nypost.com |date=2020-03-23 |accessdate=2020-03-30}}</ref>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/United States/Washington State medical cases chart}}\n\n==Timeline==\n{{see also|Life Care Centers of America#Kirkland, Washington COVID-19 outbreak}}\n\n===January: first case===\nOn January 21, the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] (CDC) confirmed the first U.S. case in a 35-year-old man living in [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]]. He had returned from [[Wuhan]], China, to the U.S., landing at [[Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport]] on January 15, without any symptoms. He reported to an urgent care clinic with symptoms of pneumonia on January 19 and was transported to [[Everett, Washington|Everett]]'s [[Providence Regional Medical Center Everett|Providence Regional Medical Center]] the following day.<ref name=\"autogenerated7\">{{cite web |url=https://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2020/p0121-novel-coronavirus-travel-case.html |title=First Travel-related Case of 2019 Novel Coronavirus Detected in United States |last=<!-- Press release; no byline--> |date=January 21, 2020 |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200121201717/https://www.cdc.gov/media/releases/2020/p0121-novel-coronavirus-travel-case.html |archive-date=January 21, 2020 |access-date=January 21, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated2\">{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/case-of-wuhan-coronavirus-detected-in-washington-state-first-in-united-states/ |title=Snohomish County man has the United States' first known case of coronavirus |last=<!--Staff and Wire Reports; no byline--> |date=January 21, 2020 |website=[[The Seattle Times]] |url-status=live |url-access=subscription |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200125164537/https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/case-of-wuhan-coronavirus-detected-in-washington-state-first-in-united-states/ |archive-date=January 25, 2020 |access-date=January 22, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Schnirring\">{{cite web |url=http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2020/01/us-detects-first-novel-coronavirus-case-traveler |title=US detects first novel coronavirus case, in traveler |last=Schnirring |first=Lisa |date=January 21, 2020 |website=Center for Infectious Disease Research and Policy, [[University of Minnesota]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200123201750/http://www.cidrap.umn.edu/news-perspective/2020/01/us-detects-first-novel-coronavirus-case-traveler |archive-date=January 23, 2020 |access-date=January 21, 2020}}</ref> He was released from the hospital on February 3 after two weeks of treatment, including the use of the anti-viral drug [[remdesivir]],<ref name=\"USA Today\">{{cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/health/2020/01/31/china-coronavirus-us-antiviral-meds-used-treat-first-patient/4622612002/ |title=First case of coronavirus in US: Patient got pneumonia, but now only has cough, study says |last=Alltucker |first=Ken |date=January 31, 2020 |website=[[USA Today]] |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200202040121/https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/health/2020/01/31/china-coronavirus-us-antiviral-meds-used-treat-first-patient/4622612002/ |archive-date=February 2, 2020 |access-date=February 1, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated6\">{{Cite journal |last=Holshue |first=Michelle L. |last2=DeBolt |first2=Chas |last3=Lindquist |first3=Scott |last4=Lofy |first4=Kathy H. |last5=Wiesman |first5=John |last6=Bruce |first6=Hollianne |last7=Spitters |first7=Christopher |last8=Ericson |first8=Keith |last9=Wilkerson |first9=Sara |last10=Tural |first10=Ahmet |last11=Diaz |first11=George |date=January 31, 2020 |title=First Case of 2019 Novel Coronavirus in the United States |journal=New England Journal of Medicine |volume=0 |issue=10 |pages=929\u2013936 |doi=10.1056/NEJMoa2001191 |issn=0028-4793 |pmid=32004427}}</ref> and went into isolation at home.<ref name=\"The Everett Herald\">{{cite web |url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/first-u-s-coronavirus-patient-released-from-everett-hospital/ |title=First U.S. coronavirus patient released from Everett hospital |date=February 3, 2020 |website=The Everett Herald |url-status=live |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200205033944/https://www.heraldnet.com/news/first-u-s-coronavirus-patient-released-from-everett-hospital/ |archive-date=February 5, 2020 |access-date=February 5, 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated6\" />\n\n===February: first deaths===\n[[File:Evergreen Hospital Emergency (2975573799).jpg|thumb|right|[[EvergreenHealth]] Medical Center in [[Kirkland, Washington|Kirkland]], Washington, where the first six U.S. deaths were reported]]\n[[File:SARS-CoV-2 and phylogenetic trees.webm|thumb|An introductory video about what the [[phylogenetic tree]] of [[SARS-CoV-2]] means for the first two sequences obtained from cases in Washington state.]]\n\nOn February 19, 2020, a resident of [[Life Care Centers of America#Kirkland, Washington COVID-19 outbreak|a Life Care Centers of America nursing home]] in [[Kirkland, Washington|Kirkland]], an [[Eastside (King County, Washington)|Eastside King County]] suburb of [[Seattle]], was transferred to a local hospital and later tested positive for COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |title='Volatile and unpredictable': Life Care Center speaks publicly for the first time since COVID-19 outbreak |first=Dyer |last=Oxley |first2=John |last2=Ryan |url=https://www.kuow.org/stories/volatile-and-unpredictable-life-care-speaks-publicly-for-the-first-time-since-covid-19-outbreak |publisher=KUOW |date=March 7, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref> On February 24, a 54-year-old man was transferred from the Life Care Center of Kirkland to [[Harborview Medical Center]] and died there on February 26. Also on the 26th, a woman in her 80s from the center died at her family home. Both were found to have had COVID-19 and in one case this was discovered in post-mortem testing.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus death toll rises to nine in Washington |first=Olivia |last=Sullivan |url=https://www.kirklandreporter.com/news/coronavirus-death-toll-rises-to-eight-in-washington/ |newspaper=Kirkland Reporter |date=March 3, 2020 |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> The two deaths were announced on March 3.<ref name=King20200301>{{cite web |title=Public Health confirms seven new COVID-19 cases, bringing overall total to 21 |url=https://www.kingcounty.gov/depts/health/news/2020/March/3-covid19-8-deaths.aspx |date=March 3, 2020 |work=kingcounty.gov |publisher=King County |access-date=March 15, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn February 28, a high school student in Everett was confirmed as having the virus. The following day, researchers confirmed the coronavirus strain in the student's case may be related to the coronavirus strain in the first confirmed U.S. case from January 19, suggesting that the virus may have been spreading in the area for up to six weeks.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus may have spread undetected for weeks in Washington state, which reported first two deaths in U.S. |first=Joel |last=Achenbach |first2=Katie |last2=Mettler |first3=Lena H. |last3=Sun |first4=Ben |last4=Guarino |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/health/coronavirus-may-have-spread-undetected-for-weeks-in-washington-state/2020/03/01/0f292336-5bcc-11ea-9055-5fa12981bbbf_story.html |newspaper=The Washington Post |date=March 2, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/01/world/coronavirus-news.html |title=Coronavirus Live Updates: New Fears Over Virus's Spread in Washington State |date=March 1, 2020 |newspaper=The New York Times  |access-date=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301055002/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/01/world/coronavirus-news.html |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Also on February 28, a woman in her 50s who had recently returned from [[South Korea]] and who was an employee of the [[United States Postal Service]] at its [[Network Distribution Center]] facility in [[Federal Way, Washington|Federal Way]], [[King County, Washington|King County]], tested positive.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://nypost.com/2020/03/01/usps-worker-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-in-seattle-area/ |title=USPS worker tests positive for coronavirus in Seattle area |last=Salo |first=Jackie |date=March 1, 2020 |website=[[The New York Post]] |url-status=live |access-date=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302000059/https://nypost.com/2020/03/01/usps-worker-tests-positive-for-coronavirus-in-seattle-area/ |archive-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.federalwaymirror.com/news/coronavirus-reaches-federal-way-as-usps-employee-tests-positive/ |title=Coronavirus reaches Federal Way as USPS employee tests positive |last=Miller |first=Madison |last2=Chastaine |first2=Danielle |date=March 1, 2020 |website=[[The Federal Way Mirror]] |url-status=live |access-date=March 1, 2020 |last3=Sullivan |first3=Olivia |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302000104/https://www.federalwaymirror.com/news/coronavirus-reaches-federal-way-as-usps-employee-tests-positive/ |archive-date=March 2, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Life Care Center of Kirkland.jpg|thumb|Life Care Center of Kirkland in 2020]]\n\nOn February 29, Washington health officials made the first announcement of a death from COVID-19 in the United States. A man in his late 50s with pre-existing chronic illness died at [[EvergreenHealth]]'s hospital in Kirkland. He was not associated with the Life Care Center and although patients from the center were also in the hospital, it was not believed that any patients contracted the virus at the hospital. Officials said there was no evidence he contracted the virus through travel and they suspected community spread of the disease in King County.<ref>{{cite news |title=Washington state man becomes first U.S. death from coronavirus |first=Nicole |last=Acevedo |first2=Minyvonne |last2=Burke |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/1st-coronavirus-death-u-s-officials-say-n1145931 |publisher=NBC News |date=March 1, 2020 |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/1st-coronavirus-death-u-s-officials-say-n1145931 |title=First coronavirus death in the U.S. happens in Washington state |first=Nicole |last=Acevedo |publisher=NBC News |date=February 29, 2020  |access-date=February 29, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229192416/https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/1st-coronavirus-death-u-s-officials-say-n1145931 |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The man had not been tested for the virus until February 28, partly because the lab in Washington had only recently become able to conduct tests, and partly because until late February the CDC had been recommending testing only for those with COVID-19 symptoms who had recently traveled to China.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.livescience.com/coronavirus-spread-washington-nursing-home.html |title=1st US death from COVID-19 reported in Washington state |first=Tia |last=Ghose |date=February 29, 2020 |work=Live Science |publisher=Future US |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref> Public health officials also reported two confirmed cases in the Life Care Center nursing home, including a woman in her 40s who was a health care worker at the facility.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.rollcall.com/2020/02/29/coronavirus-response-efforts-ramp-up-as-first-u-s-death-confirmed/ |title=Coronavirus response efforts ramp up as first U.S. death confirmed |last=Lesniewski |first=Niels |last2=Krawzak |first2=Paul M. |date=February 29, 2020 |website=[[Roll Call]] |access-date=February 29, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===March===\n====March 1\u20135====\nOn March 1, state public health officials confirmed two new cases in King County, both men in their 60s. One was hospitalized in critical condition at the [[Virginia Mason Medical Center]] in Seattle; the other was hospitalized in \"critical but stable\" condition at the [[Valley Medical Center]] in [[Renton, Washington|Renton]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kuow.org/stories/two-more-coronavirus-cases-confirmed-sunday-king-county-total-to-six |title=Two more coronavirus cases confirmed Sunday; King County total at six |last=Hiruko |first=Ashley |date=March 1, 2020 |website=[[KUOW-FM]] |access-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> Those two cases were not linked to the cases in the nursing facility that were reported on February 29.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kingcounty.gov/depts/health/news/2020/March/1-covid19-cases.aspx |title=Public Health confirms two more COVID-19 cases, bringing the total in King County to six |date=March 1, 2020 |website=KingCounty.gov  |access-date=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302145445/https://www.kingcounty.gov/depts/health/news/2020/March/1-covid19-cases.aspx |archive-date=March 2, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"CNN March 1 - Washington State\">{{cite news |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/01/health/washington-state-possible-coronavirus-outbreak/index.html |title=8 people test positive for coronavirus in Washington state |access-date=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301194042/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/01/health/washington-state-possible-coronavirus-outbreak/index.html |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Later the same day, officials reported four new cases associated with the Life Care long-term care facility: a woman in her 80s, a woman in her 90s, a man aged 70s who had died, and a man in his 70s in critical condition. Washington reported one additional case: a man in his 40s in critical condition, bringing the state's total to seven new cases reported on this day. The second death from coronavirus in the U.S. was reported at EvergreenHealth Kirkland.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/department-health-confirms-first-coronavirus-death-washington-state/XIDPHMLVOJAAREQ5YCL75367PU/ |title=Second man in King County with coronavirus dies |date=March 1, 2020 |publisher=[[KIRO-TV]] |url-status=live |access-date=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301050055/https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/department-health-confirms-first-coronavirus-death-washington-state/XIDPHMLVOJAAREQ5YCL75367PU/ |archive-date=March 1, 2020}}</ref> On March 2, officials announced another four deaths in the state, bringing the U.S. death toll to six. They also announced four new infections, bringing the state's caseload to 18, and the country's to 96.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/03/02/coronavirus-live-updates/ |title=Washington state announces 4 more coronavirus deaths more, bringing virus death toll in U.S. to 6, officials say |date=March 2, 2020 |access-date=March 2, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303034645/https://www.washingtonpost.com/world/2020/03/02/coronavirus-live-updates/ |archive-date=March 3, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> The total number of deaths in the state rose to nine on March 3.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/03/03/811690163/9-coronavirus-deaths-now-reported-in-washington-state |title=9 Coronavirus Deaths Now Reported In Washington State |publisher=NPR|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305051724/https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/03/03/811690163/9-coronavirus-deaths-now-reported-in-washington-state|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Additionally, [[Amazon.com]] confirmed that one of its Seattle employees had tested positive for coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |date=March 2, 2020|access-date=March 3, 2020 |title=Amazon employee in Seattle office tests positive for coronavirus |last=Haselton |first=Todd |publisher=[[CNBC]] |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/03/coronavirus-amazon-employee-in-seattle-office-tests-positive.html|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200304133028/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/03/coronavirus-amazon-employee-in-seattle-office-tests-positive.html|archive-date=March 4, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 4, officials reported the tenth death in the U.S. attributable to coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxnews.com/health/washington-state-confirms-coronavirus-death |title=Washington state confirms 10th coronavirus death |last=Hein |first=Alexandria |date=March 4, 2020 |publisher=Fox News Channel |access-date=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305084052/https://www.foxnews.com/health/washington-state-confirms-coronavirus-death|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> King County Public Health Department reported 10 new cases, including one death. All but one case were associated with the Life Care Centers facility.<ref>{{cite web |title=Local health officials announce new recommendations to reduce risk of spread of COVID-19 |url=https://www.kingcounty.gov/depts/health/news/2020/March/4-covid-recommendations.aspx |website=King County Public Health |accessdate=March 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305095958/https://www.kingcounty.gov/depts/health/news/2020/March/4-covid-recommendations.aspx |archive-date=March 5, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> In the evening, [[Facebook]] announced that a contractor at its Stadium East office in Seattle was diagnosed with the virus; the office was shut down until March 9 and employees were encouraged to work from home.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Wagner |first1=Kurt |title=Facebook Employee in Seattle Diagnosed With Coronavirus |url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-05/facebook-says-employee-in-seattle-diagnosed-with-coronavirus |accessdate=March 5, 2020 |work=Bloomberg |date=March 4, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305152928/https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2020-03-05/facebook-says-employee-in-seattle-diagnosed-with-coronavirus |archive-date=March 5, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On March 5, the [[Washington State Department of Health]] reported 31 new cases with the first new case reported outside of Snohomish and King counties. County case totals were Snohomish County 18, including 1 death; King County 51, including 9 deaths; [[Grant County, Washington|Grant County]] 1 case.<ref>{{cite web |date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 5, 2020 |title=2019 Novel Coronavirus Outbreak (COVID-19) |url=https://www.doh.wa.gov/Emergencies/Coronavirus|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130191908/https://www.doh.wa.gov/Emergencies/Coronavirus|archive-date=January 30, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Later, public health officials reported an additional death on March 4, bringing the state total deaths to 11.<ref>{{cite web |date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 5, 2020 |title=Public health officials confirm 11th death in Washington |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/coronavirus-daily-news-update-march-5-what-to-know-today-about-covid-19-in-the-seattle-area-washington-state-and-the-nation/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305155007/https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/coronavirus-daily-news-update-march-5-what-to-know-today-about-covid-19-in-the-seattle-area-washington-state-and-the-nation/|archive-date=March 5, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[United States Public Health Service]] (PHS) sent 28 uniformed officers to Kirkland around this time. The PHS team consisted of physicians, physicians' assistants, nurses, technicians and other medical care personnel.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[US News & World Report]]|title=Feds Send Medical 'Strike Team' to Washington State Nursing Home Hit by Coronavirus \u2013 The team was deployed to a Washington state nursing home that has emerged as the epicenter of the U.S. coronavirus outbreak.|author=Steve Sternberg|date=March 6, 2020|url=https://www.usnews.com/news/national-news/articles/2020-03-06/feds-send-medical-strike-team-to-washington-state-nursing-home-hit-by-coronavirus}}</ref>\n\n====March 6\u201310====\nOn March 6, [[Microsoft]] announced that two of its employees in Seattle, including one working remotely for subsidiary [[LinkedIn]], tested positive.<ref>{{cite web |date=March 6, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020 |title=Microsoft says two employees have been diagnosed with coronavirus |last=Novet |first=Jordan |publisher=[[CNBC]] |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/06/microsoft-says-two-employees-have-been-diagnosed-with-coronavirus.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306101743/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/06/microsoft-says-two-employees-have-been-diagnosed-with-coronavirus.html|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Three new deaths were reported in King County; all died at the EvergreenHealth Medical Center.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/coronavirus-daily-news-update-march-6-what-to-know-today-about-covid-19-in-the-seattle-area-washington-state-and-the-nation/ |title=Coronavirus daily news update, March 6: What to know today about COVID-19 in the Seattle area, Washington state and the nation|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306170137/https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/coronavirus-daily-news-update-march-6-what-to-know-today-about-covid-19-in-the-seattle-area-washington-state-and-the-nation/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> In addition, public health officials in Seattle announced that a part-time concessions employee at [[CenturyLink Field]] tested positive and may have exposed attendees of a February 22 [[Seattle Dragons]] game. The stadium, home to the [[Seattle Seahawks]], [[Seattle Sounders]], and Seattle Dragons, can seat up to 72,000 people.<ref>{{cite web |date=March 6, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020 |title=An employee at the Seattle Seahawks' stadium tested positive for coronavirus, officials say |last=Feuer |first=William |publisher=[[CNBC]] |url=https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/06/coronavirus-in-seattle-stadium-employee-tests-positive.html|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307114758/https://www.cnbc.com/2020/03/06/coronavirus-in-seattle-stadium-employee-tests-positive.html|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=March 6, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020 |title=Seattle stadium worker who worked XFL game tests positive for coronavirus |work=[[Associated Press|AP]] via [[CBS]] |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-outbreak-seattle-stadium-worker-who-worked-xfl-game-diagnosed-with-covid-19/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307055939/https://www.cbsnews.com/news/coronavirus-outbreak-seattle-stadium-worker-who-worked-xfl-game-diagnosed-with-covid-19/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=March 6, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020 |title=Part-time CenturyLink Field employee who worked for XFL Seattle Dragons game tests positive for COVID-19 |last=Reineking |first=Jim |work=[[USA Today]] |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/xfl/2020/03/05/coronavirus-stadium-employee-xfl-game-seattle-tests-positive/4970808002/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306053104/https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/xfl/2020/03/05/coronavirus-stadium-employee-xfl-game-seattle-tests-positive/4970808002/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020 |title=CenturyLink Field employee who worked Seattle Dragons' game represents low risk of coronavirus infection for attendees, officials say |last=Kamb |first=Lewis |work=[[The Seattle Times]] |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/centurylink-field-employee-who-worked-seattle-dragons-game-represents-a-low-risk-of-infection-for-game-attendees-public-health-officials-say/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306002245/https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/centurylink-field-employee-who-worked-seattle-dragons-game-represents-a-low-risk-of-infection-for-game-attendees-public-health-officials-say/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |date=March 5, 2020|access-date=March 6, 2020 |title=CenturyLink Field worker tests positive for coronavirus |publisher=[[KIRO-TV|KIRO]] |url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/centurylink-field-worker-tests-positive-coronavirus/Y4KEZPR42VCAPJWDIHHPMKWPXI/|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306233619/https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/centurylink-field-worker-tests-positive-coronavirus/Y4KEZPR42VCAPJWDIHHPMKWPXI/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The [[University of Washington]] reported that a staff member in an office away from the main campus tested positive.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washington.edu/coronavirus/2020/03/06/presumptive-positive-covid-19-test-staff-member-in-roosevelt-commons-east/ |title=Presumptive positive COVID-19 test \u2013 staff member in Roosevelt Commons East|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306170803/https://www.washington.edu/coronavirus/2020/03/06/presumptive-positive-covid-19-test-staff-member-in-roosevelt-commons-east/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Classes were to be held online starting March 9, until March 20.<ref>{{cite news |title=First U.S. Colleges Close Classrooms as Virus Spreads. More Could Follow. |first=Mike |last=Baker |first2=Anemona |last2=Hartocollis |first3=Karen |last3=Weise |newspaper=The New York Times |date=March 7, 2020 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/06/us/coronavirus-college-campus-closings.html|access-date=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307202330/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/06/us/coronavirus-college-campus-closings.html|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.washington.edu/coronavirus/2020/03/06/moving-classes-online-and-concluding-the-winter-quarter/ |title=Moving classes online and concluding the winter quarter|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306174730/https://www.washington.edu/coronavirus/2020/03/06/moving-classes-online-and-concluding-the-winter-quarter/|archive-date=March 6, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The suburban [[Northshore School District]] confirmed classes for its 23,000 students were suspended for up to two weeks.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Hobbs |first1=Jennifer Calfas and Tawnell D. |title=Schools Shut in Seattle Area as Coronavirus Spreads |url=https://www.wsj.com/articles/coronavirus-spreads-world-wide-containment-is-an-unlikely-outcome-11583403706 |accessdate=March 6, 2020 |work=The Wall Street Journal |date=March 6, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307020347/https://www.wsj.com/articles/coronavirus-spreads-world-wide-containment-is-an-unlikely-outcome-11583403706 |archive-date=March 7, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Forfeited Games and Virtual Learning: Coronavirus Shuts Down Schools |newspaper=The New York Times |first=John |last=Eligon |first2=Ellen |last2=Barry |first3=Karen |last3=Weise |date=March 9, 2020 |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/us/coronavirus-schools-san-francisco-seattle.html|access-date=March 9, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309134650/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/08/us/coronavirus-schools-san-francisco-seattle.html|archive-date=March 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> [[Starbucks]] closed one of its downtown Seattle locations after an employee tested positive.<ref>{{cite news |title=Seattle Starbucks closed after employee tests positive for coronavirus |url=https://q13fox.com/2020/03/06/seattle-starbucks-closed-coronavirus/ |work=Q13 FOX News |date=March 7, 2020  |access-date=March 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307175018/https://q13fox.com/2020/03/06/seattle-starbucks-closed-coronavirus/ |archive-date=March 7, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On March 7, the Department of Health confirmed 102 cases and 16 deaths.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/coronavirus-daily-news-update-march-7-what-to-know-today-about-covid-19-in-the-seattle-area-washington-state-and-the-nation/ |title=Coronavirus daily news update, March 7: What to know today about COVID-19 in the Seattle area, Washington state and the nation |date=March 7, 2020 |website=The Seattle Times |access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> EvergreenHealth announced its 13th coronavirus death, bringing the total in Washington State to 17 deaths.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.yaktrinews.com/covid-19-washington-state-death-toll-climbs-to-17/ |title=COVID-19 Washington state death toll climbs to 17 |access-date=March 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309001422/https://www.yaktrinews.com/covid-19-washington-state-death-toll-climbs-to-17/ |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Clark County announced its first positive test of the coronavirus in a man in his 70s.<ref>{{cite news |title=Clark Co. Health confirms first coronavirus case |last=KOIN 6 News Staff |url=https://www.koin.com/news/health/coronavirus/clark-co-health-confirms-first-coronavirus-case/ |publisher=KOIN 6 News |date=March 6, 2020 |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 8, the Washington State Department of Health confirmed 136 cases and 18 deaths, mainly in King County. Later in the day, after the department of health report, an additional death was reported in Grant County.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/coronavirus-daily-news-update-march-8-what-to-know-today-about-covid-19-in-the-seattle-area-washington-state-and-the-nation/ |title=Coronavirus daily news update, March 8: What to know today about COVID-19 in the Seattle area, Washington state and the nation |date=March 8, 2020 |website=The Seattle Times |access-date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> In the Seattle area, a staff member of the Aegis Living Marymoor assisted living facility in [[Redmond, Washington|Redmond]] tested positive. The staff member has been isolated since February 28 after reporting symptoms. All Aegis Living communities are limiting non-essential visits. This is the fourth senior living facility in the Seattle area to report staff members who test positive.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/coronavirus-daily-news-update-march-7-what-to-know-today-about-covid-19-in-the-seattle-area-washington-state-and-the-nation/ |title=Seattle Times staff (7 March 2020) Aegis Living Marymoor staff member tests positive for COVID-19 |access-date=March 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309002332/https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/coronavirus-daily-news-update-march-7-what-to-know-today-about-covid-19-in-the-seattle-area-washington-state-and-the-nation/ |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Kitsap County reported its first positive test, a [[Bainbridge Island]] resident in their 60s who was being kept in isolation.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Kitsap Sun |location=Bremerton, Washington |title=First 'presumptive positive' coronavirus case reported in Kitsap County |first=Nathan |last=Pilling |date=March 8, 2020 |url=https://www.kitsapsun.com/story/news/2020/03/08/first-presumptive-positive-covid-19-case-reported-kitsap/4997808002/|access-date=March 10, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309190328/https://www.kitsapsun.com/story/news/2020/03/08/first-presumptive-positive-covid-19-case-reported-kitsap/4997808002/|archive-date=March 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> On March 9, the Washington State Department of Health reported 26 new cases and 3 new deaths as cases continued to appear in new counties.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/coronavirus-daily-news-update-march-9-what-to-know-today-about-covid-19-in-the-seattle-area-washington-state-and-the-nation/ |title=Live: Coronavirus daily news update, March 9: What to know today about COVID-19 in the Seattle area, Washington state and the nation |date=March 9, 2020 |website=The Seattle Times |access-date=March 9, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309192018/https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/coronavirus-daily-news-update-march-9-what-to-know-today-about-covid-19-in-the-seattle-area-washington-state-and-the-nation/|archive-date=March 9, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.doh.wa.gov/emergencies/coronavirus |title=Novel Coronavirus Outbreak 2020 :: Washington State Department of Health |date=March 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309215710/https://www.doh.wa.gov/emergencies/coronavirus |access-date=March 9, 2020|archive-date=March 9, 2020 }}</ref> This brought the total deaths in Washington to 22.{{citation needed|date=March 2020}} Life Care Center of Kirkland reported that 31 of its patients had tested positive.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: New test results find 31 positive cases at Life Care Center in Kirkland |date=March 9, 2020 |work=Q13 Fox News |agency=Associated Press |url=https://q13fox.com/2020/03/09/coronavirus-new-test-results-find-31-positive-cases-at-life-care-center-in-kirkland/}}</ref> (City of) Snohomish schools would be closed beginning March 10 after a transportation employee was tested positive.<ref>{{cite news |title=Snohomish, Meridian school districts, several Tacoma schools closing after positive coronavirus tests |publisher=[[KCPQ]] |date=March 9, 2020 |url=https://q13fox.com/2020/03/09/snohomish-school-district-several-tacoma-schools-closing-after-positive-coronavirus-tests/}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, the Washington State Department of Health reported an additional 105 cases, a 62% increase. Two additional deaths were reported in King County, in two separate nursing homes unconnected to the Life Care Center nursing home where most deaths have been reported. This brought the state total deaths to 24 with the majority, 22, in King County.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/coronavirus-daily-news-update-march-10-what-to-know-today-about-covid-19-in-the-seattle-area-washington-state-and-the-nation/ |title=Live: Coronavirus daily news update, March 10: What to know today about COVID-19 in the Seattle area, Washington state and the nation |date=March 10, 2020 |website=The Seattle Times |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> Whatcom County declared a public health emergency after it reported its first case of the virus. The female patient self-isolated at home after receiving treatment at a local [[Bellingham, Washington|Bellingham]] medical center.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.bellinghamherald.com/news/local/article241075056.html |title=Coronavirus: Whatcom County declares emergency for COVID-19 |date=March 10, 2020 |website=The Bellingham Herald |access-date=March 10, 2020}}</ref> [[Island County]] reported its first positive test.<ref>{{cite web |title=Press Release: March 10, 2020 |publisher=Island County Public Health |date=March 10, 2020 |url=https://www.islandcountywa.gov/Health/Pages/COVID-19.aspx}}</ref> [[Skagit County]] reported its first positive test.<ref>{{cite news |title=Skagit County's first case of COVID-19 confirmed |first=Brandon |last=Stone |newspaper=[[Skagit Valley Herald]] |location=Mount Vernon, Washington |date=March 10, 2020 |url=https://www.goskagit.com/news/skagit-county-s-first-case-of-covid--confirmed/article_772a96af-8ab1-59aa-bb00-2b997d8b4073.html}}</ref>\n\n====March 11\u201315====\nOn March 11, five new deaths were reported, bringing the total to 29.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.doh.wa.gov/Emergencies/Coronavirus |title=2019 Novel Coronavirus Outbreak (COVID-19) March 11th |website=doh.wa.gov|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200311212910/https://www.doh.wa.gov/Emergencies/Coronavirus|archive-date=March 11, 2020|access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> [[Thurston County, Washington|Thurston County]] reported its first confirmed case.<ref>{{cite press release |publisher=Thurston County Public Health and Social Services |date=March 11, 2020 |title=Public Health Confirms Case of COVID-19 in Thurston County |url=https://www.thurstoncountywa.gov/tchome/pages/newsreleasedetail.aspx?List-ID=2044}}</ref>\n\n[[Columbia County, Washington|Columbia County]] and [[Yakima County, Washington|Yakima County]] reported first cases on March 12.<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus cases reported in Yakima, Columbia counties |newspaper=Tri-City Herald |date=March 12, 2020 |url=https://www.tri-cityherald.com/news/local/article241109661.html}}</ref> On March 13, Governor Inslee ordered all public and private schools closed for six weeks.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/2020/mar/13/spokane-health-officer-orders-cancellations-of-lar/|title=Inslee closes all schools starting March 17 through April 24 &#124; The Spokesman-Review|website=www.spokesman.com}}</ref> On March 14, the Washington State Department of Health (DOH) confirmed three cases in [[Spokane County]] residents.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://srhd.org/news/2020/spokane-county-covid-19-pui-update |publisher=Spokane Regional Health District |title=COVID-19 confirmed in Spokane County residents |date=March 14, 2020}}</ref> On March 15, the American College of Emergency Physicians announced that an emergency physician at EvergreenHealth Medical Center in Kirkland was in critical condition with COVID-19.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The New York Times |title=Two Emergency Room Doctors Are in Critical Condition With Coronavirus |first=Karen |last=Weise |date=March 15, 2020 |url=https://nyti.ms/38OLKBL}}</ref> [[Lewis County, Washington|Lewis County]] announced their first case on March 15, with the patient being quarantined in a [[Cowlitz County, Washington|Cowlitz County]] hospital.<ref>{{cite web |type=press release |title=First COVID-19 case identified in Lewis County |publisher=Lewis County Public Health & Social Services |date=March 15, 2020 |url=https://lewiscountywa.gov/departments/public-health/blog/first-covid-19-case-identified-lewis-county/}}</ref><ref name=KPTV20200315>{{cite news |title=First case of COVID-19 reported in Cowlitz County |publisher=[[KPTV]] |location=Portland, Oregon |date=March 15, 2020 |url=https://www.kptv.com/news/first-case-of-covid--reported-in-cowlitz-county/article_1549f36a-6745-11ea-b81e-4ffb06c89662.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://tdn.com/news/local/first-coronavirus-case-at-st-john-is-an-elderly-lewis/article_99fadf16-ed8a-530c-b659-eaa15964c1a2.html |title=First coronavirus case at St. John is an elderly Lewis County resident |first1=Katie|last1=Fairbanks |first2=Andre|last2= Stepankowsky |website=Longview Daily News |access-date=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\n====March 16\u201320====\nOn March 16, two deaths occurred in Clark County, a husband and wife that lived in separate elder care facilities. Also, a Seattle resident <!-- Jennifer Haller-->was the first U.S. volunteer to receive a [[COVID-19 vaccine|vaccine for the virus that causes COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |via=KIRO |title=Coronavirus vaccine test opens as US volunteer gets 1st shot |first=Lauran |last=Neergaard |first2=Carla K. |last2=Johnson |date=March 16, 2020 |url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/coronavirus-vaccine-test-opens-us-volunteer-gets-1st-shot/7ZMDSWJD6VBJVKFRL5TONVYLKE/}}</ref> [[Mason County, Washington|Mason County]] reported its first case on March 17, an individual who was being quarantined at home.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=Kitsap Sun |location=Bremerton, Washington |title=Mason County sees first positive COVID-19 test |date=March 17, 2020|url=https://www.kitsapsun.com/story/news/2020/03/17/mason-county-sees-first-positive-test-covid-19/5075195002/}}</ref> The first case in [[Franklin County, Washington|Franklin County]] was announced on March 17: a woman in her 20s with underlying health conditions. The Benton\u2013Franklin Health District said the case was linked to foreign travel.<ref>{{cite web |website=Official website |publisher=Benton\u2013Franklin Health District |date=March 17, 2020 |title=BFHD Announces First Local Case of COVID-19 |url=https://www.bfhd.wa.gov/news/what_s_new/b_f_h_d_announces_first_local_case_of_c_o_v_i_d-19}}</ref> The first two confirmed cases in [[Chelan County, Washington|Chelan County]] were reported, from [[Leavenworth, Washington|Leavenworth]] and [[Chelan, Washington|Chelan]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Chelan, Leavenworth men test positive for COVID-19 |first=Reilly |last=Kneedler |newspaper=[[Wenatchee World]] |date=March 17, 2020 |url=https://www.wenatcheeworld.com/news/coronavirus/chelan-leavenworth-men-test-positive-for-covid/article_f579ee78-686b-11ea-a2ee-db2e221581c6.html}}</ref> On March 18, the death of a [[Richland, Washington|Richland]] woman in her 80s, a [[retirement community]] resident with underlying health conditions, was announced as Benton\u2013Franklin Health District's first COVID-19 related death.<ref>{{cite web |website=Official website |publisher=Benton\u2013Franklin Health District |date=March 18, 2020 |title=BFHD Announces 1st Confirmed COVID-19 Death |url=https://www.bfhd.wa.gov/news/what_s_new/b_f_h_d_announces_1st_confirmed_c_o_v_i_d-19_death}}</ref> It was the second death in [[Eastern Washington]], after Grant County.<ref>{{cite news |title=Spokane County confirms 5th COVID-19 case; 2nd Eastern Washington death reported |date=March 18, 2020 |newspaper=Spokesman-Review |location=Spokane |url=https://www.spokesman.com/stories/2020/mar/18/spokane-county-confirms-5th-covid-19-case-health-o/}}</ref>\n\n[[Clallam County, Washington|Clallam County]] reported its first case, a man in his 60s being isolated at home, on March 19.<ref>{{cite news |title=Clallam County sees first COVID-19 case, Coho ferry service suspended |first=Paul |last=Gottlieb |newspaper=[[Peninsula Daily News]] |location=Port Angeles, Washington |date=March 19, 2020 |url=https://www.peninsuladailynews.com/news/clallam-county-sees-its-first-covid-19-case/}}</ref> The Northeast Tri-County Health District reported the first case in [[Stevens County, Washington|Stevens County]] on March 20,<ref>{{cite news|publisher=[[KHQ-TV]]|location=Spokane|title=Stevens County resident tests positive for COVID-19\n|date=March 20, 2020|url=https://www.khq.com/coronavirus/stevens-county-resident-tests-positive-for-covid/article_41357448-6ad0-11ea-a593-ef1bf9d79d70.html}}</ref> and [[San Juan County, Washington|San Juan County]] reported its first case the same day: an individual who was treated at the [[Eastsound, Washington|Eastsound]] UW Medicine clinic.<ref>{{cite news|title=Orcas resident first person diagnosed with COVID-19 in San Juan County|newspaper=Islands' Sounder|publisher=[[Sound Publishing]]|url=https://www.islandssounder.com/news/orcas-man-first-person-diagnosed-with-covid-19-in-san-juan-county/}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|publisher=San Juan County, Washington|website=official website|title=COVID-19 DATA FOR SAN JUAN COUNTY|date=March 20, 2020|url=https://www.sanjuanco.com/1682/COVID-19-SJC-Case-Count}}</ref> The Washington Distillers Guild announced it was converting from producing drinkable liquor to [[hand sanitizer]],<ref>{{cite news|publisher=KIRO|location=Seattle|title=Coronavirus in Washington state: A timeline of the outbreak \u2013 March 19|first=Casey|last=McNerthney|date=March 19, 2020|url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/coronavirus-washington-state-timeline-outbreak/IM65JK66N5BYTIAPZ3FUZSKMUE/}}</ref> joining many other distilleries in the United States doing so after regulations were waived by the U.S. Department of Treasury's [[Alcohol and Tobacco Tax and Trade Bureau]].<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=The New York Times|title=Distilleries Race to Make Hand Sanitizer Amid Coronavirus Pandemic|first=Michael|last=Levenson|date=March 19, 2020|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/19/us/distilleries-virus-hand-sanitizer.html}}</ref>\n\n====March 21\u201331====\n[[Walla Walla County]] and [[Adams County, Washington|Adams County]] reported their first cases March 21,<ref>{{cite news|title=First case of COVID-19 confirmed in Walla Walla County\n|author=Vicki Hillhouse |newspaper=[[Walla Walla Union-Bulletin]]|date= March 21, 2020|url=https://www.union-bulletin.com/news/health_fitness/coronavirus/first-case-of-covid--confirmed-in-walla-walla-county/article_814a385c-5684-571d-adb0-990bf22b73b9.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=First person tests positive for COVID-19 in Adams County|date=March 21, 2020|author=Emily Oliver|publisher=[[KXLY-TV]]|location=Spokane|url=https://www.kxly.com/first-person-tests-positive-for-covid-19-in-adams-county/}}</ref>\nand [[Whitman County, Washington|Whitman County]] reported its first case March 22.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.khq.com/coronavirus/woman-becomes-first-whitman-county-resident-to-test-positive-for/article_3fca7cda-6c69-11ea-ae67-83d8506c6281.html|title=Woman becomes first Whitman County resident to test positive for COVID-19|website=KHQ Right Now|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> [[Douglas County, Washington|Douglas County]] reported its first case March 23.<ref>{{cite news|title=Four new COVID-19 cases reported, including first in Douglas County|author=Reilly Kneedler|newspaper=Wenatchee World|location=Wenatchee, Washington|date=March 23, 2020|url=https://www.wenatcheeworld.com/news/coronavirus/four-new-covid--cases-reported-including-first-in-douglas/article_800a8792-6d39-11ea-a5c0-e7023efa815c.html}}</ref> [[Okanogan County]] and [[Ferry County]] reported their first COVID-19 cases on March 24 and 25.<ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Omak Chronicle|title=Okanogan County gets its first COVID-19 case|date=March 24, 2020|url=https://www.omakchronicle.com/free/okanogan-county-gets-its-first-covid--case/article_4fe2b0f6-6e35-11ea-91d5-976e6330c10d.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|newspaper=Omak Chronicle|title=Ferry County gets its first COVID-19 case|date=March 25, 2020|url=https://www.omakchronicle.com/free/ferry-county-gets-its-first-covid--case/article_74df0586-6ec0-11ea-a64e-fbd38c6a9b85.html}}</ref>\n\nRadio station KUOW announced that starting March 25, it would no longer broadcast President Trump's briefings on the coronavirus \"due to a pattern of false or misleading information provided that cannot be fact checked in real time\".<ref>{{cite web |author1=J. Edward Moreno |title=Washington state radio station won't air Trump briefings because of 'false or misleading information' |url=https://thehill.com/blogs/news/blog-briefing-room/489439-seattle-radio-station-wont-air-trump-briefings-because-of-false-or |publisher=The Hill |accessdate=31 March 2020 |date=25 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Skamania County]] reported its first case on March 26.<ref>{{cite news|title=Skamania County confirms first case of COVID-19, needs personal protective equipment for first responders|author=Kelly Moyer | date=March 26, 2020 | newspaper=Camas-Washougal Post-Record | location= Camas, Washington |url=https://www.camaspostrecord.com/news/2020/mar/26/skamania-county-confirms-first-case-of-covid-19-needs-personal-protective-equipment-for-first-responders/ }}</ref>\n\nOn March 28, medics from the U.S. Army converted [[CenturyLink Field]], known for being the home stadium of the [[Seattle Seahawks]], into a medical hospital.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000001107811/article/centurylink-field-to-host-military-hospital-amid-virus |title=CenturyLink Field to host military hospital amid virus |publisher=NFL.com |date= |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/coronavirus-department-health-reports-coronavirus-data-glitches-army-sets-up-shop/XIDPHMLVOJAAREQ5YCL75367PU/|title=Coronavirus: Department of Health reports coronavirus data glitches as Army sets up shop|first=KIRO 7 News|last=Staff|website=KIRO}}</ref>\n\n===April===\n{{Expand section|date=April 2020}}\n\n==Government response==\n[[File:Pence at Washington EOC.jpg|thumb|United States Vice President [[Mike Pence]] at [[Washington State Emergency Operations Center]]]]\nOn February 29, Governor [[Jay Inslee]] declared a state of emergency after the first US death attributable to COVID-19 occurred in a man in his 50s with an underlying chronic health condition who had been admitted to [[EvergreenHealth]] Medical Center after complaining of severe breathing problems.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Brownstone |first1=Sydney |last2=Cornwell |first2=Paige |last3=Lindblom |first3=Mike |last4=Takahama |first4=Elise |date=February 29, 2020 |title=King County patient is first in U.S. to die of COVID-19 as officials scramble to stem spread of novel coronavirus |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/one-king-county-patient-has-died-due-to-covid-19-infection/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200229211513/https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/one-king-county-patient-has-died-due-to-covid-19-infection/ |archive-date=February 29, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> In a statement, Inslee said, \"It is a sad day in our state as we learn that a Washingtonian has died from COVID-19. Our hearts go out to their family and friends. We will continue to work toward a day where no one dies from this virus.\"<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/rachelsandler/2020/02/29/washington-state-reports-1st-us-coronavirus-death-declares-statewide-emergency/ |title=Washington State Reports 1st U.S. Coronavirus Death, Declares Statewide Emergency |last=Sandler |first=Rachel |work=Forbes |access-date=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301080551/https://www.forbes.com/sites/rachelsandler/2020/02/29/washington-state-reports-1st-us-coronavirus-death-declares-statewide-emergency/#28dc3a2218f0 |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> A second man in his 70s died at the same hospital a day later, the second US death attributable to COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite news |last=Hudetz |first=Mary |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/officials-2-men-in-king-county-being-treated-for-covid-19/ |title=Number of COVID-19 cases in King County jumps to 10; new coronavirus may have circulated for weeks |date=March 1, 2020 |work=The Seattle Times |access-date=March 1, 2020 |last2=Carter |first2=Mike |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302032603/https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/officials-2-men-in-king-county-being-treated-for-covid-19/ |archive-date=March 2, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> By March 2, the death toll in the Seattle area had risen to six,<ref>[https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/coronavirus-death-toll-rises-6-200302203641200.html US coronavirus death toll rises to 6] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200302235440/https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/coronavirus-death-toll-rises-6-200302203641200.html |date=March 2, 2020 }}, [[Al Jazeera]], March 2, 2020. Retrieved March 3, 2020.</ref> nine by March 3<ref>{{cite news |first=Bill |last=Chappell |title=9 Coronavirus Deaths Now Reported In Washington State |url=https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/03/03/811690163/9-coronavirus-deaths-now-reported-in-washington-state |publisher=NPR |date=March 2, 2020 |accessdate=March 4, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200303234555/https://www.npr.org/sections/health-shots/2020/03/03/811690163/9-coronavirus-deaths-now-reported-in-washington-state|archive-date=March 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> 11 by March 5,<ref name=\"March 5\" /> and 18 by March 8.<ref>{{cite news |title=King County reports 2 more coronavirus deaths, bringing statewide total to 18 |url=https://q13fox.com/2020/03/08/king-county-reports-2-more-coronavirus-deaths-bringing-statewide-total-to-18/ |work=Q13 FOX News |date=March 8, 2020  |access-date=March 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200309053332/https://q13fox.com/2020/03/08/king-county-reports-2-more-coronavirus-deaths-bringing-statewide-total-to-18/ |archive-date=March 9, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nResearchers at the [[Fred Hutchinson Cancer Research Center]] and the [[University of Washington]] analyzed the genomes of the first reported case in [[Snohomish County, Washington|Snohomish County]] from January 20 and a more recent case on February 28, and determined that the [[virus strain]] was related. Their findings indicate that the virus may have been spreading through the community for close to six weeks.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/01/health/coronavirus-washington-spread.html |title=Coronavirus May Have Spread in U.S. for Weeks, Gene Sequencing Suggests |last=Fink |first=Sheri |last2=Baker |first2=Mike |newspaper=The New York Times |access-date=March 1, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200301210826/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/01/health/coronavirus-washington-spread.html |archive-date=March 1, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> A drive-through testing facility was opened by the [[University of Washington Medical Center]] in North Seattle, which as of March 10 is only open to students and employees.<ref>{{cite news |title=First drive-thru coronavirus testing facility in the U.S. opens in Seattle |url=https://www.cbsnews.com/news/drive-thru-coronavirus-testing-facility-us-seattle-washington/ |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |publisher=CBS News}}</ref>\n\nSeattle mayor [[Jenny Durkan]] declared a civil emergency on March 3.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://durkan.seattle.gov/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2020/03/COVID-19https://durkan.seattle.gov/wp-content/uploads/sites/9/2020/03/COVID-19-Mayoral-Proclamation-of-Civil-Emergency.pdf-Mayoral-Proclamation-of-Civil-Emergency.pdf |title=Mayoral Proclamation of Civil Emergency |website=City of Seattle |publisher=City of Seattle | access-date=March 3, 2020 | url-status=live}}</ref> On March 3, [[Public Health \u2013 Seattle & King County]] began establishing the [[White Center COVID-19 quarantine site]]. On March 5, United States Vice President [[Mike Pence]] visited the state governor at [[Washington State Emergency Operations Center]] on [[Camp Murray]], north of the state capital [[Olympia, Washington|Olympia]]<!-- note some sources incorrectly say he visited Olympia-->, to discuss the crisis.<ref>{{cite news |agency=Associated Press |title=Pence walks fine line on coronavirus response |first=Aamer |last=Madhani |date=March 7, 2020 |url=https://apnews.com/19376394fdac9b7e700a5ef51ff6ad6e|access-date=March 7, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307164352/https://apnews.com/19376394fdac9b7e700a5ef51ff6ad6e|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release |title=Vice President Pence, Congresswoman Herrera Beutler Visit Pierce County Readiness Center and Washington State Emergency Operations Center |date=March 6, 2020 |publisher=Office of U.S. Rep. [[Jaime Herrera Beutler]] |url=https://herrerabeutler.house.gov/news/documentsingle.aspx?DocumentID=401804}}</ref> On March 5, the number of confirmed cases jumped from 39 the previous day to 70, of which 51 are in King County and 18 in Snohomish County.<ref name=\"March 5\">{{cite news |author=KIRO 7 News Staff|title=Coronavirus: Washington cases increase to 70; death toll increases to 11 |url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/coronavirus-washington-cases-increase-70-death-toll-increases-11/XIDPHMLVOJAAREQ5YCL75367PU/ |accessdate=March 5, 2020 |publisher=KIRO |date=March 5, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305211822/https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/coronavirus-washington-cases-increase-70-death-toll-increases-11/XIDPHMLVOJAAREQ5YCL75367PU/ |archive-date=March 5, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> On March 5, Inslee announced that the state will cover the costs of testing for Washington residents without health insurance. At a news briefing with Inslee, Vice President Pence said that [[Air Force Two]] delivered 100,000 air-filtering N95 respirators, 100,000 surgical masks and 2,500 face shields to Washington.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.geekwire.com/2020/washington-state-takes-steps-cut-costs-coronavirus-testing-treatment/ |title=Washington Gov. Inslee cuts coronavirus costs \u2014 and meets with VP Mike Pence |date=March 6, 2020 |website=GeekWire |access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307151909/https://www.geekwire.com/2020/washington-state-takes-steps-cut-costs-coronavirus-testing-treatment/|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> The same day, Washington's insurance commissioner, [[Mike Kreidler]] issued an emergency order to state health insurers requiring them to waive [[Copayment|copays]] and [[deductible]]s for any consumer requiring coronavirus testing, effective until May 4.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.insurance.wa.gov/news/kreidler-orders-washington-health-insurers-waive-deductibles-and-copays-coronavirus-testing |title=Kreidler orders Washington health insurers to waive deductibles and copays for coronavirus testing {{!}} Washington state Office of the Insurance Commissioner|website=insurance.wa.gov|access-date=March 6, 2020|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307051944/https://www.insurance.wa.gov/news/kreidler-orders-washington-health-insurers-waive-deductibles-and-copays-coronavirus-testing|archive-date=March 7, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 9, Governor Inslee announced new rules\u2014including mandatory screening for visitors and staff\u2014for nursing homes to slow the spread of the virus. The state was also considering mandatory measures of [[social distancing]] to prevent spread.<ref>{{cite news |author=KIRO 7 News Staff|title=Coronavirus: Inslee announces new rules for nursing homes, assisted living facilities |url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/coronavirus-inslee-announces-new-rules-nursing-homes-assisted-living-facilities/XIDPHMLVOJAAREQ5YCL75367PU/ |accessdate=March 10, 2020 |publisher=KIRO |date=March 9, 2020}}</ref> The governor's office announced that workers who have reduced hours or temporary unemployment due to the outbreak are eligible for [[unemployment benefits]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Zdanowicz |first1=Christina |title=Restaurants struggle to survive as coronavirus turns Seattle into a ghost town |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/10/us/seattle-restaurants-customer-decrease-trnd/index.html |accessdate=March 11, 2020 |publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, Governor Inslee invoked emergency powers and banned \"social, spiritual, and\nrecreational gatherings\" of over 250 people in King, Snohomish and Pierce Counties (including the core of the [[Seattle metropolitan area]]) for at least the month of March.<ref name=ESPN0311>{{cite news |publisher=[[ESPN]] |title=Washington Gov. Jay Inslee bans large gatherings in Seattle area, including sporting events |date=March 11, 2020 |url=https://www.espn.com/espn/story/_/id/28881392/washington-gov-jay-inslee-ban-large-gatherings-seattle-area-including-sporting-events}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |publisher=KUOW |title=Large events banned in Seattle area amid efforts to slow COVID-19 spread |first=Liz |last=Brazile |date=March 11, 2020 |url=https://www.kuow.org/stories/large-events-banned-in-seattle-area-amid-efforts-to-slow-covid-19-spread}}</ref> The order included provisions for its enforcement by the [[Washington Military Department]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.governor.wa.gov/sites/default/files/20-07%20Coronavirus%20%28tmp%29.pdf |title=PROCLAMATION 20-07 BY THE GOVERNOR, AMENDING PROCLAMATIONS 20-05 AND 20-06 |author=signed by Jay Inslee |publisher=Governor's office of the State of Washington |date=March 11, 2020 |quote=As a result of this event, I continue to order into active state service the organized militia of Washington State to include the National Guard and the State Guard, or such part thereof as may be necessary in the opinion of The Adjutant General to address the circumstances described above, to perform such duties as directed by competent authority of the Washington State Military Department in addressing the outbreak.}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, Governor Inslee announced closures for all public and private K-12 schools in King, Snohomish, and Pierce Counties beginning from March 17 through at least April 24.<ref>{{cite web |title=Inslee announces school closures in King, Snohomish and Pierce counties |url=https://www.governor.wa.gov/news-media/inslee-announces-school-closures-king-snohomish-and-pierce%C2%A0counties |website=governor.wa.gov |accessdate=March 13, 2020}}</ref> Later, on March 13, Inslee announced K-12 closures until at least April 24 throughout the state.<ref>{{cite web |website=Official website |publisher=Governor Jay Inslee |date=March 14, 2020 |title=Inslee announces statewide school closures, expansion of limits on large gatherings |url=https://medium.com/wagovernor/inslee-announces-statewide-school-closures-expansion-of-limits-on-large-gatherings-63d442111438 |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\nLocal transit agencies in the Seattle area, including [[King County Metro]] and [[Sound Transit]], announced more frequent deep cleanings of their vehicles and facilities.<ref>{{cite news |last=Baruchman |first=Michelle |date=March 1, 2020 |title=What Seattle area public transit riders should know about the novel coronavirus |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/transportation/what-seattle-area-public-transit-riders-should-know-about-the-novel-coronavirus/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> Within the first week of widespread work-from-home policies from local employers, Sound Transit ridership dropped 25 percent and Metro reported a 13 percent decrease compared to March 2019.<ref>{{cite news |last=Lindblom |first=Mike |date=March 12, 2020 |title=As ridership drops, should Seattle-area transit agencies trim service amid coronavirus outbreak? |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/transportation/as-ridership-drops-should-seattle-area-transit-agencies-trim-service-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Switzer |first=Jeff |date=March 13, 2020 |title=March 13: Metro ridership decreases as public heeds direction of public health officials |url=https://kingcountymetro.blog/2020/03/13/march-13-metro-ridership-decreases-as-public-heeds-direction-of-public-health-officials/ |work=Metro Matters |publisher=King County Metro |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref> Metro and Sound Transit also announced the temporary suspension of [[proof of payment|fare enforcement]] on buses and trains to reduce person-to-person contact.<ref>{{cite news |last=Craighead |first=Callie |date=March 13, 2020 |title=King County Metro and Sound Transit temporarily suspend fare enforcement amid COVID-19 outbreak |url=https://www.seattlepi.com/local/seattlenews/article/Metro-suspends-fare-enforcement-coronavirus-15129329.php |work=Seattle Post-Intelligencer |accessdate=March 15, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 15, Governor Inslee announced the closing of all sit-down restaurants statewide, noting that \"very strong measures are necessary to slow the spread of the disease\". Restaurants are still allowed to offer takeout and drive through options.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Schnell |first1=Lindsay |title=California, Ohio, Illinois, Massachusetts and Washington close bars and restaurants in effort to slow coronavirus |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/nation/2020/03/15/coronavirus-bars-restaurants-closed-states/5055634002/ |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=USA Today}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=LIST: States that have closed restaurants and bars to dine-in customers |url=https://cbs4indy.com/news/list-states-that-have-closed-restaurants-and-bars-to-dine-in-customers/ |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |work=WTTV CBS4Indy |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> The governor also announced that he would issue an emergency proclamation ordering all entertainment and recreation facilities to temporarily close.<ref>{{cite news |last1=La Corte |first1=Rachel |title=Inslee to order all bars/restaurants to close to fight virus |url=https://apnews.com/b8cff05b257bb2ad621a2c844c30b95a |accessdate=March 15, 2020 |agency=Associated Press |date=March 15, 2020}}</ref> The same order banned gatherings of groups of 50 or more statewide.<ref>{{cite news |title=Washington state to shut down restaurants, bars, and cap gatherings at 50 to stop spread of coronavirus |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=March 15, 2020 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/king-county-and-washington-state-to-act-on-bars-restaurants-and-gatherings/}}</ref>\n\nOn March 16, Mayor Jenny Durkan announced $5 million in grocery vouchers for families impacted by COVID-19.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Derrick |first1=Anthony |title=Mayor Jenny Durkan Announces $5 Million in Grocery Vouchers for Families Impacted by COVID-19 |url=https://durkan.seattle.gov/2020/03/mayor-jenny-durkan-announces-5-million-in-grocery-vouchers-for-families-impacted-by-covid-19/ |website=Office of the Mayor |accessdate=March 16, 2020 |date=March 16, 2020}}</ref> The city created the program to provide 6,250 families $800 each with vouchers for Safeway stores in Washington state. Also, the Seattle Police Department announced the suspension of all police front counter services and that public access to precinct and headquarters police facilities would be curtailed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Effective Immediately: Police Precincts and Headquarters Closed to Public |url=https://spdblotter.seattle.gov/2020/03/16/effective-immediately-police-precincts-and-headquarters-closed-to-public/ |website=spdblotter.seattle.gov |publisher=Seattle Police Department |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>  A correctional officer at the King County Correctional Facility in Seattle tested positive for COVID-19 on March 16.  He was last at work on March 8.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=King County Department of Adult & Juvenile Detention |title=Department of Adult & Juvenile Detention |url=https://www.kingcounty.gov/depts/jails.aspx |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 17, the Seattle City Council unanimously passed a moratorium on residential evictions.  Mayor Durkan used her emergency powers to prohibit evictions on the basis of rent delinquency for 30 days or due to expiring leases.<ref>{{cite news |title=Seattle's coronavirus moratorium on residential evictions is approved, expanded by City Council |first=Daniel |last=Beekman |work=The Seattle Times |date=March 17, 2020 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/politics/seattles-coronavirus-moratorium-on-residential-evictions-is-approved-expanded-by-city-council/}}</ref> The City Council expanded this to cover all evictions except when the health or safety of others is imminently threatened by tenant actions.  The moratorium also prohibits late fees for tenants struggling to make rent payments.<ref>{{cite news |last=Graham |first=Nathalie |date=March 17, 2020 |title=Seattle City Council Expands Eviction Moratorium, Paid Sick Leave |url=https://www.thestranger.com/slog/2020/03/17/43169566/seattle-city-council-expands-eviction-moratorium-paid-sick-leave |work=The Stranger |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>  Starting on March 17, King County correctional facilities stopped accepting people arrested for violating their state Department of Corrections community supervision; and is planning to transfer anyone in a King County correctional facility under such a warrant back to state custody.  As of March 20, there were 180 such people in King County correctional facilities that may get transferred out.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Public Health - Seattle & King County |title=Additional testing capacity, adjustments at King County jails, and other COVID-19 updates from Public Health - Seattle & King County for March 20, 2020 |url=https://www.kingcounty.gov/depts/health/news/2020/March/20-covid.aspx |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 18, the King County government began preparing the first of several [[field hospital]]s on a soccer field in [[Shoreline, Washington|Shoreline]] that is anticipated to have 200 beds for coronavirus patients.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bush |first=Evan |date=March 18, 2020 |title=King County to put 200-bed field hospital on Shoreline soccer field amid coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/health/king-county-to-put-200-bed-field-hospital-on-shoreline-soccer-field-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe neighboring [[Canada|Canadian]] province of [[British Columbia]] ordered curtailment of meetings over 50 people on March 16.<ref>{{cite news |title=B.C. cancelling events with more than 50 people |first=Andrew |last=Weichel |publisher=[[CTV News]] |location=Vancouver, BC|date=March 16, 2020 |url=https://bc.ctvnews.ca/b-c-cancelling-events-with-more-than-50-people-1.4855058}}</ref>\n\nOn March 21, the City of Everett ordered residents and business owners to stay at home \"until further notice\", except for some essential workers.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=KING-TV|title=Everett mayor issues stay at home directive to help stop spread of coronavirus|author=Kaila Lafferty|date=March 21, 2020|url=https://www.king5.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/everett-mayor-issues-stay-at-home-directive-to-help-stop-spread-of-coronavirus/281-490e7b78-2450-4ecf-a02c-8faa9cb2fb57}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, President Donald Trump said the federal government would pay the costs of activation of the [[Washington National Guard]] while under control of the state governor.<ref>{{cite news|title=Trump outlines national guard activations for New York, California and Washington|author=Paul LeBlanc|publisher=CNN|date=March 22, 2020|url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/22/politics/trump-coronavirus-task-force-briefing/index.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Coronavirus: Trump approves Washington's emergency disaster declaration, approves use of National Guard|publisher=KIRO-TV|url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/coronavirus-trump-approves-washingtons-emergency-disaster-declaration/XIDPHMLVOJAAREQ5YCL75367PU/}}</ref>\n\nOn March 22, 2020, retired Navy admiral [[Raquel C. Bono]] was named by Washington State Governor [[Jay Inslee]] to lead the state's health system response to the pandemic.<ref name=KIRO>{{cite news|publisher=[[KIRO-TV]]|location=Seattle|title=Inslee naming retired vice admiral to direct state's health system response|author=KIRO 7 News Staff|agency=Associated Press|url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/inslee-naming-retired-vice-admiral-direct-states-health-system-response/OXWFFZ46UJHFTG46QOJWHYPF4A/}}</ref> President Donald Trump also announced approval of Washington emergency declaration, and have instructed Federal assistance to be given to assist the local recovery efforts in fighting the coronavirus.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.whitehouse.gov/briefings-statements/president-donald-j-trump-approves-washington-disaster-declaration-2/|title=President Donald J. Trump Approves Washington Disaster Declaration|website=The White House|language=en-US|access-date=2020-03-23}}</ref>\n\nGovernor Inslee announced a statewide stay-at-home order on March 23, to last at least two weeks.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Associated Press|title=Washington governor issues two-week stay-at-home order|author=Rachel La Corte|date=March 23, 2020|url=https://apnews.com/5abcb144b6d0f106436e67c7930a5243}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, 2020, King County Executive [[Dow Constantine]] signed an Executive Order suspending the Department of Adult & Juvenile Detention's Work Education Release program.  Additionally, King County correctional facilities will no longer accept people due to misdemeanor charges, except for assaults, violations of no contact or protection orders, DUIs, sex crimes or other charges which present a serious public safety concern.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=King County |title=Quickly, safely reducing the jail population so staff can ensure the health of everyone in correctional facilities |url=https://www.kingcounty.gov/elected/executive/constantine/news/release/2020/March/24-jail-population.aspx |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Washington State Parks]] system was closed on March 25, and access to [[Washington State Department of Natural Resources|Department of Natural Resources]] land closed on March 26.<ref name=Sanders20200325>{{cite news|newspaper=Everett Herald|title=City, state, federal parks mostly closed due to COVID-19\n|quote=Even the remotest trails on state Department of Natural Resources land are closing to the public.|author=Julia-Grace Sanders|date=March 25, 2020|url=https://www.heraldnet.com/news/city-state-federal-parks-mostly-closed-due-to-covid-19/}}</ref> Most roads into [[Olympic National Park]] were also closed, as well as all facilities.<ref name=Sanders20200325/> Roads in [[Mount Rainier National Park]] were closed March 24, although \"dispersed recreation\" in the backcountry was allowed.<ref>{{cite news|title=Mount Rainier National Park closed to the public to help slow spread of coronavirus|author=Stacia Glenn|newspaper=Tacoma News-Tribune|date=March 24, 2020 |url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/news/local/crime/article241476076.html}}</ref>\n\nOn March 27, Seattle Mayor [[Jenny Durkan]] announced that the [[United States Army Corps of Engineers]] and [[Federal Emergency Management Agency]] agreed to deploy a military field hospital at [[CenturyLink Field]].  The field hospital is expected to create at least 150 hopsital beds for non-COVID-19 patients; and will be staffed by 300 soldiers from the 627th Army Hospital from [[Fort Carson]], Colorado.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=City of Seattle |title=U.S. Army Brings Field Hospital to Seattle to Help Reduce Burden on Local Hospitals |url=https://durkan.seattle.gov/2020/03/u-s-army-brings-field-hospital-to-seattle-to-help-reduce-burden-on-local-hospitals/ |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |publisher=Army Times|title=Three Army field hospitals ordered to New York, Washington states |accessdate=March 28, 2020 |url=https://www.armytimes.com/news/your-army/2020/03/24/three-army-field-hospitals-ordered-to-new-york-washington-states/}}</ref>  On March 28, the [[Port of Seattle]] and the [[Northwest Seaport Alliance]] made plans to make sections of Terminal 46 available for trailers, container equipment and storage needs in support of the US Army Field Hospital being setup at CenturyLink Field.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Port of Seattle |title=Port, NWSA to Make Sections of Terminal 46 Available to Support U.S. Army Field Hospital |url=https://www.portseattle.org/news/port-nwsa-make-sections-terminal-46-available-support-us-army-field-hospital |accessdate=March 28, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Delay in data reporting==\nAs of March 31, 2020 technical difficulties involving the Department of Health and [[Power BI|Microsoft Power BI]] are causing a delay in the timely reporting of coronavirus data to the public. The last reported data is from March 28, 2020 and is now a couple of days out of date.<ref name=official_DOH_COVID/> However, most counties are reporting timely data which give a fairly good picture. [[King County]] data, however, is also delayed in connection with the statewide delay, although normal reporting is expected to resume on April 1.<ref name=\"kc-data-dashboard\">{{cite web |url=https://www.kingcounty.gov/depts/health/communicable-diseases/disease-control/novel-coronavirus/data-dashboard.aspx |title=COVID-19 data dashboard - King County |publisher=King County |date=March 31, 2020 |accessdate=March 31, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Economic and social effects==\n[[File:Paramount Theatre in Seattle with postponement marquee, March 2020.jpg|thumb|right|The marquee of the [[Paramount Theatre (Seattle)|Paramount Theatre]] in Seattle, announcing postponement of all events]]\nSeveral national media outlets reported that fewer Seattle residents were observed outside in public places in early March.<ref>{{cite news |last=Weise |first=Karen |date=March 5, 2020 |title='It's a Weird Feeling': Seattle Hunkers Down Amid Coronavirus Outbreak |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/05/us/seattle-stays-home.html |newspaper=The New York Times |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307001753/https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/05/us/seattle-stays-home.html |archive-date=March 7, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=In the middle of a coronavirus outbreak, people of Seattle adjust to changes |url=https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/06/us/seattle-changing-life-coronavirus/index.html |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |publisher=CNN |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200307063506/https://www.cnn.com/2020/03/06/us/seattle-changing-life-coronavirus/index.html |archive-date=March 7, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Local businesses, especially in tourist areas, reported fewer customers and sales.<ref>{{cite news |last=Moorer |first=Brit |date=March 5, 2020 |title=Did the coronavirus turn Seattle into a ghost town? Businesses react to recent headline |url=https://www.king5.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/is-seattle-a-ghost-town-businesses-react-recent-report/281-cdc72690-cee7-424d-bdd3-474edab22308 |publisher=KING 5 News |accessdate=March 7, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200306195715/https://www.king5.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/is-seattle-a-ghost-town-businesses-react-recent-report/281-cdc72690-cee7-424d-bdd3-474edab22308 |archive-date=March 6, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn March 10, Seattle-based [[Alaska Airlines]] announced the company was preparing to cut its flight schedule and freeze hiring due to the sharp drop in airline bookings because of the pandemic.<ref>{{cite news |title='Breathtaking' drop in air travel due to coronavirus has Alaska, Southwest preparing to cut flights |first=Dominic |last=Gates |newspaper=The Seattle Times |date=March 11, 2020 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/boeing-aerospace/alaska-southwest-battered-by-decline-in-air-travel-due-to-coronavirus-prepare-to-cut-flights/}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, the city of Seattle announced that the [[Seattle Public Library|public library system]], [[community center]]s, and other recreation facilities would be closed until at least April 13.<ref>{{cite news |last=Beekman |first=Daniel |date=March 12, 2020 |title=Seattle closing all public libraries, community centers, parks programs in bid to slow coronavirus |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/seattle-closing-all-public-libraries-community-centers-parks-programs-in-bid-to-slow-coronavirus/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref> Other libraries in the state followed suit, including [[Sno-Isle Libraries]], the [[King County Library System]], the [[Pierce County Library System]], and the [[North Central Regional Library]].<ref>{{cite news |date=March 14, 2020 |title=Seattle/King County Public Health Update on Coronavirus: Durkan Signs Emergency Order to Halt Evictions |url=https://southseattleemerald.com/2020/03/11/seattle-king-county-public-health-update-on-coronavirus/ |work=South Seattle Emerald |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Utter |first=Joe |date=March 13, 2020 |title=North Central Regional Library closing library branches, effective Monday |url=http://www.ifiberone.com/columbia_basin/north-central-regional-library-closing-library-branches-effective-monday/article_24c3aa7c-659a-11ea-ae00-5fb62fdae578.html |publisher=iFiber One |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\n[[Unibail-Rodamco-Westfield|Westfield]] closed all its malls \u2013 including [[Westfield Southcenter]], the largest shopping mall in Washington state and the Pacific Northwest \u2013 on March 19.<ref>{{cite news |title=Westfield Southcenter mall in Tukwila closes because of coronavirus |first=Steve |last=Hunter |date=March 19, 2020 |newspaper=Kent Reporter |publisher=[[Sound Publishing]] |url=https://www.kentreporter.com/business/westfield-southcenter-mall-in-tukwila-closes-because-of-coronavirus/}}</ref> [[Bellevue Square]] and [[Lincoln Square (Bellevue)|Lincoln Square]] had closed the day before.<ref>{{cite news |work=[[425 Magazine]] |title=The Bellevue Collection Temporarily Closes Retail |first=Zoe |last=Branch |date=March 17, 2020 |url=https://425magazine.com/the-bellevue-collection-temporarily-closes-retail/}}</ref>\n\n[[Boeing]] announced on March 23\u201324 that all manufacturing facilities in the Puget Sound area and the [[Grant County International Airport]] [[737 Max]] storage and testing facility in Moses Lake would be closed for two weeks, starting March 25.<ref>{{cite news|publisher=Associated Press|title=Boeing to suspend production in Seattle because of virus\n|author=Martha Billisle|author2=Rachel La Corte|url=https://apnews.com/90fd863092dab407beae44085625f629}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|publisher=iFiberOne News|location=Ephrata, Washington|title=Boeing to suspend Moses Lake operations due to COVID-19, Delta sending sidelined planes to local airport|date=March 24, 2020|url=http://www.ifiberone.com/columbia_basin/boeing-to-suspend-moses-lake-operations-due-to-covid-/article_8e6aba9a-6e0c-11ea-80e5-93895695a91b.html}}</ref>\n\nRetail closures not subject to the March 23 stay-at-home edict included retail pharmaceutical providers and [[Cannabis in Washington (state)|retail cannabis]] and alcohol providers, considered an essential need by the order.<ref>{{cite news|title=Yes, pot shops and liquor stores are 'essential businesses' in Washington|publisher=KREM-TV|location=Spokane|date=March 24, 2020|url=https://www.krem.com/article/news/health/coronavirus/pot-shops-liquor-stores-essential-washington/293-4d52621e-ee33-4575-9dde-62b4edc511f3}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|website=State of Washington official coronavirus website|title=What's open and closed: essential business|url=https://coronavirus.wa.gov/whats-open-and-closed/essential-business|accessdate=March 25, 2020}}</ref> Breweries were also considered essential and some offered curbside pickup.<ref>{{cite news|title=Why are Washington state breweries considered 'essential' during the coronavirus pandemic?|author=Kristine Sherred|newspaper=Tacoma News Tribune|date=March 26, 2020|url=https://www.thenewstribune.com/entertainment/restaurants/tnt-diner/article241482901.html}}</ref>\n\n===School closures===\n[[File:Stevens Elementary School during COVID epidemic 05.jpg|thumb|left|Playground at a Seattle elementary school is closed due to the epidemic on 25 March]]\nOn March 4, [[Northshore School District]] became the first school district in the state to announce an extended district-wide closure due to the pandemic, shifting to remote online learning. The closure was initially scheduled to last up to 14 days.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.nsd.org/covid19/message/~board/superintendent-blog/post/letter-to-families-all-schools-closed-march-5 |title=Letter to Families: All School Sites Closing March 5 |date=March 4, 2020  |access-date=March 18, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The Seattle Times |title=Northshore School District closes all schools for coronavirus concerns: 'We are no longer able to provide quality instruction' |first=Elise |last=Takahama |date=March 4, 2020 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/education/northshore-school-district-closes-all-schools-beginning-thursday-school-will-resume-online-monday/}}</ref>\n\nThe two largest state universities, [[University of Washington]] (UW) and [[Washington State University]] (WSU) curtailed on-campus classes during the pandemic. UW announced its closure on March 6; and on March 11, WSU announced the closure would begin after its spring break, on March 23.<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[Tri-City Herald]] |location=Kennewick, Washington |title=WSU cancels in-person classes after spring break because of coronavirus outbreak |first=Cameron |last=Probert |date=March 11, 2020 |url=https://www.tri-cityherald.com/news/local/education/article241098801.html}}</ref>\n\nOn March 11, school districts in the Greater Seattle area, including [[Seattle Public Schools]], [[Lake Washington School District]], and [[Bellevue School District]], announced their closures shortly after Governor [[Jay Inslee]]'s social distancing proclamation in the morning.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.seattleschools.org/district/calendars/news/what_s_new/coronavirus_update |title=Coronavirus Update: All Schools Closed Starting March 12 |date=March 11, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.lwsd.org/programs-and-services/health-services/coronavirus-information |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19) Information: March 11, 2020 |date=March 11, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://bsd405.org/corona-virus-covid-19/ |title=Coronavirus (COVID-19): March 11, 2020 |date=March 11, 2020 |access-date=March 11, 2020}}</ref> Many school districts in Snohomish County announced closures starting March 13, including [[Snohomish School District]], [[Monroe School District]], and [[Marysville School District]]. Others announced closures for 14 days or more starting on March 16 including [[Everett School District]] and [[Edmonds School District]].<ref>{{cite news |publisher=KCPQ |title=Here are the latest school closures in western Washington amid coronavirus concerns |date=March 11, 2020 |url=https://q13fox.com/2020/03/11/here-are-the-latest-coronavirus-closures-in-western-washington/}}</ref>\n\nOn March 12, the governor invoked his emergency power and mandated the closure of all private and public schools in King, Pierce and Snohomish Counties, through April 24 or later; the next day, he expanded the closure to all K-12 schools statewide.<ref>{{cite news |title=Inslee expands coronavirus K-12 school closure, 250-person gathering ban, across Washington |first=Hannah |last=Ferraro |author2=Joseph O\u2019Sullivan |first3=Neal |last3=Morton |first4=Dahlia |last4=Bazzaz |work=The Seattle Times |date=March 12, 2020 |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/education-lab/inslee-announces-all-washington-k-12-schools-to-close-in-an-effort-to-slow-the-spread-of-coronavirus/}}</ref>\n\nAll [[Thurston County, Washington|Thurston County]] schools, and [[Shelton School District]] (the largest district in [[Mason County, Washington|Mason County]]) announced their closures beginning March 16, through at least April 24.<ref>{{cite news |publisher=iFiberOne News Radio |title=SHELTON SCHOOL DISTRICT - All Schools Closed Starting Monday, March 16th |date=March 13, 2020 |url=http://www.ifiberonenewsradio.com/news/local_news/shelton-school-district---all-schools-closed-starting-monday/article_5aceb008-656d-11ea-933d-abef5bf13b03.html}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |newspaper=The Olympian |title=All Thurston County schools will close starting Monday and into April for coronavirus |first=Sara |last=Gentzler |date=March 13, 2020 |url=https://www.theolympian.com/news/local/article241175941.html}}</ref>\n\n===Sports===\nMany scheduled public events went on as planned, including a [[Major League Soccer]] fixture between the [[Seattle Sounders FC]] and [[Columbus Crew SC]] at [[CenturyLink Field]] on March 7. It was played in front of a crowd of 33,080, making it the smallest crowd to ever attend a regular season MLS match in Sounders history.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Booth |first1=Tim |title=Smaller crowd for Seattle's 1st major event since outbreak |date=March 7, 2020 |url=https://apnews.com/a433b5c026e147a4e760ef9fb6f5b2ca |agency=Associated Press |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308015643/https://apnews.com/a433b5c026e147a4e760ef9fb6f5b2ca |archive-date=March 8, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> Pundits attributed the lower attendance to the coronavirus as immunocompromized fans and others who did not want to attend the match due to the outbreak were offered full refunds.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Oshan |first1=Jeremiah |title=Coronavirus concerns leave Sounders weighing difficult options |url=https://www.sounderatheart.com/2020/3/4/21165289/seattle-sounders-coronavirus-options |website=Sounder at Heart |publisher=SB Nation |accessdate=March 8, 2020 |date=March 4, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Brewer |first=Jerry |date=March 8, 2020 |title=In Seattle, a soccer match during the coronavirus feels both routine and extraordinary |url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/in-seattle-a-soccer-match-during-the-coronavirus-feels-both-routine-and-extraordinary/2020/03/08/53292550-60c6-11ea-b014-4fafa866bb81_story.html |work=The Washington Post |accessdate=March 9, 2020 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200308232007/https://www.washingtonpost.com/sports/in-seattle-a-soccer-match-during-the-coronavirus-feels-both-routine-and-extraordinary/2020/03/08/53292550-60c6-11ea-b014-4fafa866bb81_story.html |archive-date=March 8, 2020 |url-status=live}}</ref> [[ESPN]] noted the effect the governor's ban on gatherings in Puget Sound area would have on sports, especially if it should be expanded to Eastern Washington; the first round of the [[2020 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament]] was scheduled to be held in Spokane in March.<ref name=ESPN0311/> NCAA basketball was subsequently cancelled altogether. On March 12, [[Major League Baseball]] cancelled the remainder of [[spring training]], and on March 16, they announced that the season will be postponed indefinitely, after the recommendations from the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention|CDC]] to restrict events of more than 50 people for the next eight weeks, affecting the [[2020 Seattle Mariners season|Seattle Mariners]].<ref name=\"mlb\">{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/opening-of-regular-season-to-be-pushed-back |title=Opening of regular season to be pushed back |first=Mark |last=Feinsand |publisher=[[Major League Baseball]] |date=March 16, 2020 |access-date=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Arts and media===\nSeattle Artists Relief Fund was established to help artists, especially in the performing arts, cope with the loss of patrons due to the pandemic-related shutdowns.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=City of Seattle |title=COVID-19 resources for the community: Worker/Artist Support |url=http://www.seattle.gov/mayor/covid-19 |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref> Included in the closures were the [[Pacific Northwest Ballet]] and the [[Seattle Symphony]].<ref>{{cite news |newspaper=[[Crosscut.com]] |title=Things to Do (to support the arts right now) \u2013 After coronavirus cancellations, Seattle's creative economy needs help. |first=Brangien |last=Davis |first2=Margo |last2=Vansynghel |first3=Agueda Pacheco |last3=Flores |first4=Misha |last4=Berson |date=March 12, 2020 |url=https://crosscut.com/2020/03/things-do-support-arts-right-now}}</ref>\n\nMost of the state's newspapers removed [[paywall]]s for COVID-19 information, including ''The Seattle Times'', the ''Tacoma News Tribune'', ''Bellingham Herald'', ''Peninsula Daily News'', ''The Olympian'', ''Tri City Herald'', ''Wenatchee World'', ''The Columbian'', ''The Spokesman-Review'', and the ''Yakima Herald-Republic''.<ref>{{cite tweet |user=GovInslee |number=1238143585276424192 |date=March 12, 2020 |title=Many WA news sites have made their COVID-19 coverage free.}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=GovInslee |number=1238221381805850624 |date=March 12, 2020 |title=I'm also grateful to the @Yakima_Herald for taking down the paywall on their COVID-19 coverage.}}</ref><ref>{{cite tweet |user=GovInslee |number=1238152003311697920 |date=March 12, 2020 |title=Thanks to @thecolumbian and @SpokesmanReview for dropping their paywall on COVID-19 coverage, as well.}}</ref> ''The Seattle Times'' was praised for its early coverage of the outbreak, including public service announcements and question-and-answer sessions with readers.<ref>{{cite news |last=Bauder |first=David |date=March 11, 2020 |title=Coronavirus story provides chance to push service journalism |url=https://apnews.com/07aa21c9e2dc2f5312c86ba8f7c303ac |agency=[[Associated Press]] |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref> ''[[The Stranger (newspaper)|The Stranger]]'', an alt-weekly newspaper in Seattle, announced a temporary layoff of 18 employees to offset ad revenue losses due to the closure of restaurants and entertainment venues.<ref>{{cite news |last=Frizelle |first=Christopher |date=March 13, 2020 |title=The Stranger Temporarily Lays Off 18 Employees |url=https://www.thestranger.com/slog/2020/03/13/43143769/the-stranger-temporarily-lays-off-18-employees |work=The Stranger |accessdate=March 14, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24th, a public radio station in the state, [[KUOW-FM]], announced it would no longer broadcast the White House press briefings on the coronavirus \"due to a pattern of false or misleading information provided that cannot be fact checked in real time.\" Nevertheless, KUOW stated that it will continue to provide relevant information and news regarding the pandemic from the press briefings.<ref>{{cite news |title=Washington state radio station won't air Trump briefings because of 'false or misleading information' |url=https://thehill.com/blogs/news/blog-briefing-room/489439-seattle-radio-station-wont-air-trump-briefings-because-of-false-or |agency=The Hill |date=March 25, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Tourism and entertainment===\n[[File:Undeployed chairs in a Vancouver restaurant, March 2020.jpg|thumb|Interior of Vancouver, Washington restaurant open for takeout only on March 16]]\nThe economic loss to the region due to canceled cruise ship visitors to Seattle was unknown as of mid March, with the [[Port of Seattle]] \"exploring options.\" The industry brings in nearly one billion dollars<!-- KIRO --> annually to the Puget Sound area, with the Alaska cruise season considered to start April 1.<ref>{{cite news |publisher=KOMO |title='Exploring all of our options': COVID-19 threatens Seattle cruise season |first=Nick |last=Popham |date=March 9, 2020 |url=https://komonews.com/news/coronavirus/exploring-all-of-our-options-covid-19-threatens-seattle-cruise-season}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |publisher=KIRO |title=Port of Seattle: Start of 2020 cruise season could be delayed amid coronavirus concerns |first=Michael |last=Spears |date=March 8, 2020 |url=https://www.kiro7.com/news/local/port-seattle-start-2020-cruise-season-could-be-delayed-amid-coronavirus-concerns/WR4K22XDRFD4ZIBCIUOFXLGXDE/}}</ref>  On March 11, 2020, the Port of Seattle announced the cancellations of April 1 and 5 planned cruise ship sailings.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Port of Seattle |title=Port Cancels First Two Sailings of Seattle Cruise Season |url=https://www.portseattle.org/news/port-cancels-first-two-sailings-seattle-cruise-season |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>  On March 13, 2020, the Government of Canada deferred the start of their cruise ship season to July 1, 2020.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Government of Canada |title=Government of Canada announces intention to defer the start of cruise ship season in Canada as COVID-19 response measure |date=March 13, 2020 |url=https://www.canada.ca/en/transport-canada/news/2020/03/government-of-canada-announces-intention-to-defer-the-start-of-cruise-ship-season-in-canada-as-covid-19-response-measure.html |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref> As noted by the Port of Seattle, \"United States maritime laws require foreign flagged vessels, which include many cruise ships, to stop at a foreign port on a U.S. port to U.S. port itinerary. This is why most Seattle to Alaska cruise itineraries visit Victoria, and changes in Canada can impact Seattle-based cruises.\"<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Port of Seattle |title=Statement on Canadian Suspension of Cruise until July 1 |url=https://www.portseattle.org/news/statement-canadian-suspension-cruise-until-july-1 |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>  On March 14, 2020, the [[Centers for Disease Control and Prevention]] issued a 30-day no sail order impacting all cruise ships subject to U.S. jurisdiction.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |title=Cruise Ship Guidance |date=March 15, 2020 |url=https://www.cdc.gov/quarantine/cruise/index.html |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |publisher=Centers for Disease Control and Prevention |title=NO SAIL ORDER AND OTHER MEASURES RELATED TO OPERATIONS |url=https://www.cdc.gov/quarantine/pdf/signed-manifest-order_031520.pdf |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\nThe landmark [[Space Needle]] closed on March 13 through March 31.<ref>{{cite news |publisher=KCPQ |title=Space Needle suspends operations through March 31 amid COVID-19 pandemic |date=March 12, 2020 |url=https://q13fox.com/2020/03/12/space-needle-suspends-operations-through-march-31-amid-covid-19-pandemic/}}</ref> Many of the vendors at [[Pike Place Market]]\u2014those who sell nonessential items\u2014closed on March 23 following the statewide stay-at-home order, but some food vendors remained open as of March 31.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Fremson |first1=Ruth |title=No Crowds. No Flying Fish. Coronavirus Empties Pike Place Market. |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2020/03/31/us/coronavirus-seattle-market.html?action=click&module=News&pgtype=Homepage |accessdate=31 March 2020 |work=The New York Times |date=31 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nSeveral major conventions, including the [[Emerald City Comic Con]] at the [[Washington State Convention Center]] in Seattle, were cancelled or postponed in response to the coronavirus crisis.<ref name=\"Times-Rescheduled\">{{cite news |last=Talbott |first=Chris |date=March 16, 2020 |title=Emerald City Comic Con organizers work to reschedule a number of shows as coronavirus outbreak spreads |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/entertainment/events/emerald-city-comic-con-organizers-work-to-reschedule-a-number-of-shows-as-coronavirus-outbreak-spreads/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last=Khasimova Long |first=Katherine |date=March 11, 2020 |title=Lost wages, difficult spring for Seattle-area hospitality workers as coronavirus causes canceled events |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/business/events-canceled-due-to-coronavirus-mean-lost-wages-difficult-spring-for-seattle-area-hospitality-workers/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref>\n\nMany Western Washington tribal casinos announced their closures on March 16, although not subject to the state government proclamations. Closures were at the Muckleshoot, Puyallup, Snoqualmie, Suquamish and Tulalip casinos in King, Kitsap, Pierce, and Snohomish Counties.<ref>{{cite news |last=Mapes |first=Lynda V. |date=March 16, 2020 |title=Some Puget Sound region tribes shutting down casinos to slow spread of coronavirus |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/suquamish-tribe-shutting-down-its-casino-to-contain-spread-of-coronavirus-more-casino-closures-expected/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 16, 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |publisher=KCPQ |location=Tacoma |title=Several western Washington casinos closing amid coronavirus outbreak |url=https://q13fox.com/2020/03/16/several-western-washington-casinos-closing-amid-coronavirus-outbreak/}}</ref>\n\n===Travel and transportation===\n\nSeveral [[public transit]] agencies in Western Washington announced cuts to service and free fares to avoid contact between passengers and drivers. [[King County Metro]], the largest operator serving Seattle, will reduce service and suspend the [[South Lake Union Streetcar]].<ref>{{cite news |last=Groover |first=Heidi |date=March 19, 2020 |title=Metro, Sound Transit slash service, citing coronavirus outbreak |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/transportation/sound-transit-to-reduce-rail-bus-service-due-to-coronavirus-outbreak/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref> Large agencies in the Puget Sound region are also anticipating a decline in revenue from [[sales tax]]es, which would cause delays or changes to major projects.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lindblom |first1=Mike |last2=Groover |first2=Heidi |date=March 19, 2020 |title=Sound Transit, Metro facing big drops in funding as coronavirus downturn takes hold |url=https://www.seattletimes.com/seattle-news/transportation/sound-transit-metro-facing-big-drops-in-funding-as-coronavirus-downturn-takes-hold/ |work=The Seattle Times |accessdate=March 19, 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn March 24, 2020, the Port of Seattle stated that a [[Transportation Security Administration]] security officer working at [[Seattle\u2013Tacoma International Airport]] had tested positive for COVID-19.  The officer had last worked on March 21 at Checkpoint 5 which would now be closed for cleaning.<ref>{{cite web |publisher=Port of Seattle |title=TSA Officer at SEA Tests Positive for COVID-19 |url=https://www.portseattle.org/news/tsa-officer-sea-tests-positive-covid-19 |accessdate=March 24, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Cases by county==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:right\"\n! colspan=5 | Coronavirus disease 2019 (COVID-19) cases in Washington\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" | County\n! scope=\"col\" | Confirmed cases\n! scope=\"col\" | Deceased\n! scope=\"col\" | Recoveries\n! scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Notes\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Adams\n| 14\n| 0\n| 3\n| Updated: 03/31/20<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.co.adams.wa.us/government/covid-19.php |title=COVID 19 cases increase to 14, residents urged to stay home RITZVILLE ndash As COVID 19 continues to spread across Central and Eastern Washington, three cases have been confirmed in Lind |publisher=Co.adams.wa.us |date=2020-01-21 |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Asotin\n| 0\n| 0\n| ?\n| Updated: 6:00 pm  03/31/20 <ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asotincountypublichealth.org |title=Asotin County Health District - Home |publisher=Asotincountypublichealth.org |date= |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Benton\n| 108\n| 7\n| ?\n|Updated: 1:00 pm  04/01/20<ref name=\"bfhd.wa.gov\">{{cite web|url=https://www.bfhd.wa.gov/cms/One.aspx?portalId=10766056&pageId=16584954 |title=COVID-19 Case Count - Benton Franklin Health District |publisher=Bfhd.wa.gov |date=2020-03-26 |accessdate=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:left;\" | Chelan\n| 17\n| 2\n| ?\n|Updated: 5:00 pm  03/31/20<ref>{{cite web|author=Veronica Farias|url=https://cdhd.wa.gov/covid-19/#case-count |title=COVID-19 \u2013 Chelan-Douglas Health District |publisher=Cd